/the-10th-tv-series-craze-awards-2019.html|title=The 10TH TV Series Craze Awards 2019 - The Full List of Winners! |date=January 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| Fastest Rising Boygroup\n| {{Won}} \n|-\n| align=\"center\"| Push Awards\n| align=\"center\"| \"Go Up\"\n| align=\"center\"| Original Song of the Year\n| {{Nominated}} \n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pushawards.abs-cbn.com/|title=Push Awards Year 5|date=2019-11-15|website=abs-cbn|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"| Music Rank Extra Awards\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"| SB19\n| align=\"center\"| Asia's Boy Group\n| {{Pending}} \n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://musicrank.wixsite.com/vote|title=Music Rank Extra Awards 2020|date=January 23, 2020 |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| Next Big Thing\n| {{Pending}} \n|-\n| align=\"center\"| #MREAwards Top Social Artist\n| {{Pending}} \n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2020 Box Office Entertainment Awards|Box Office Entertainment Awards]]\n| align=\"center\"| Promising Recording/Performing Group\n| {{won}} \n|<ref>{{cite web |first=Nora V. |last=Calderon |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/149220/kathryn-bernardo-alden-richards-box-office-entertainment-awards-a742-20200207/|title=Official List Of Recipients: 51st Box Office Entertainment Awards winners |publisher=pep.ph |accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|sb19official|SB19}}\n* {{Instagram|officialsb19|SB19}}\n* {{Twitter|sb19official|SB19}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Filipino boy bands]]\n[[Category:Filipino pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2018]]\n__FORCETOC__\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:c185:5700:4159:f6ba:f044:8a11", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SB19"}
{"title_page": "Zimbabwe men's national field hockey team", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox national field hockey team\n| name          = Zimbabwe\n| association   = [[Hockey Association of Zimbabwe]]\n| confederation = [[African Hockey Federation|AfHF]] ([[Africa]])\n| coach         = N Milner\n| manager       = C Lapham\n| captain       = T Maredza\n| founded       = 1964\n| region        = Zimbabwe\n| rank          = {{FIH World Rankings|ZIM}}\n| max rank = 41\n| max date = 2003\n| min rank = 70\n| min date = January 2017\n| home ground   = [[Khumalo Hockey Stadium]]\n<!-- First kit colors -->\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 =_blacksides\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| leftarm1 = FF0000\n| body1 = FF0000\n| rightarm1 = FF0000\n| shorts1 = FF0000\n| socks1 = FF0000\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport |Men's [[Field Hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ZIM}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[All-Africa Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1987 All-Africa Games|1987 Nairobi]]| [[1987 All-Africa Games|Team Competition]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1991 All-Africa Games|1991 Cairo]]| [[1991 All-Africa Games|Team Competition]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Hockey Africa Cup of Nations]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Hockey Africa Cup of Nations|2000 Bulawayo]]| [[Hockey Africa Cup of Nations|Team Competition]]}}\n}}\nThe '''Zimbabwe men's national field hockey team''' is the team that represents [[Zimbabwe]] in the sport of [[field hockey]]. Field hockey has the second biggest player base in the country after football. Currently, Zimbabwe has four pitches, two in Bulawayo \u2013 one water base and one sand filled \u2013 and another sand filled at the Arundel School and water base at St John's College in the capital city of Harare. Bulawayo has approximately 1,000 hockey players and Harare 8,000. The 5,000-capacity [[Khumalo Hockey Stadium]]<ref>http://www.worldstadiums.com/africa/countries/zimbabwe.shtml</ref> in [[Bulawayo]] is their home stadium. Field hockey club '''Skies Hockey Club''' also use the venue for home games. They are currently ranked 61st in [[FIH World Rankings|International hockey ranking]].  While the country had a tradition in the sport,  they struggled in recent times largely due to their inability to participate in international competitions organized by the African Hockey Federation (AfHF) and the International Hockey Federation (FIH), until the Khumalo Hockey Stadium was refurbished and played host to the 2011 African Olympic Qualifier.\n\nThe governing body for field hockey is [[Hockey Association of Zimbabwe]]. It was formed in 1925.\n\n==Medals table==\n\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = \n | event          = \n | team           = \n | gold_AAA = 0 | silver_AAA = 1 | bronze_AAA = 1 | name_AAA = [[Field hockey at the African Games|All-Africa Games]]\n | gold_BBB = 0 | silver_BBB = 0 | bronze_BBB = 1 | name_BBB = [[Hockey Africa Cup of Nations]]\n | gold_CCC = 0 | silver_CCC = 1 | bronze_CCC = 0 | name_CCC = [[African Hockey Cup of Championship]]\n}}\n\n==History==\n===Early Years===\nBack when the country was [[Rhodesia]], the national hockey team qualified for the [[Field hockey at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964 Olympics in Tokyo]] after beating the [[United Arab Republic]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/29/archives/olympic-field-hockey-berth-eyed-by-southern-rhodesia.html | title=Olympic Field Hockey Berth Eyed by Southern Rhodesia | date=29 March 1964 | newspaper=The New York Times | page=S4 | accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> Team captain [[Lloyd Koch]] was [[1964 Summer Olympics national flag bearers|Rhodesia's flag bearer]],<ref>https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5150/5150.html</ref> and \nthe team won one game over New Zealand. Koch scored two goals in the tournament.\n\n===1980's \u2013 Rise in Africa after Independence===\n[[Zimbabwe]] got independence in 1980. Soon after independence, various attempts were made to establish sports in the country. [[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team|Women's team]] won the inaugural Gold medal in [[Field hockey at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Olympics]]. Men's team picked the graph and went on to perform decent in the International games. They won silver and bronze medals in 1987 and 1991 [[All-Africa Games]] respectively. The team also bagged bronze medal in [[Hockey African Cup for Nations]] in 2000 by defeating [[Ghana men's national field hockey team|Ghana]]. They managed to hold a strong position in the African continent for almost two decades.\n\n===Decline and re-establishment=== \nZimbabwe saw a drought in sports after the year 2000. They couldn't manage to maintain their spot in the African region and fall down to sixth in the continental ranking. To revive the game of hockey in the country, [[2011 African Olympic Qualifier (field hockey)|2011 African Olympic Qualifier]] were organised in Zimbabwe. But the problem was the stadium was not ready by that time. [[Hockey Association of Zimbabwe|Zimbabwe]] asked help from [[South African Hockey Association|South Africa]]. On 8 July 2011 The Hockey Association of Zimbabwe announced that the ship with the containers holding the new carpet for the Khumalo Hockey Stadium (KHS) was due to dock in Durban, South Africa. Chairman of the Hockey Olympic Qualifiers local organising committee Gavin Stephens said in a statement that the carpet should be delivered to Bulawayo by 16 July.\n\n\"This will keep the project on course for commissioning by the end of July. It is understood that the Ministry of Public Works is rushing to meet the deadline, with their work schedule lagging behind.\"\n\nIn response to a call from the Matabeleland Hockey Board (MHB), approximately 60\u201370 people arrived at the Khumalo Hockey Stadium on Saturday, 2 July 2011. About 20 of these were labourers from Petra School, Burger & McBean and Precast Concrete Products. The other 50 were made up of hockey players, parents of hockey players, and members of general public.\n\nThe Minister of Education, Sport, Arts and Culture, David Coltart, arrived to lend his support, while both current and former national and provincial hockey players were also present. Zimbabwe performed poorly in the tournament and lost 4 out of 5 games with a draw against Morocco. \nLater on, Zimbabwe hosted African Hockey Club of Championship in 2014 and won silver medal after losing to [[Kenya men's national field hockey team|Kenya]] by 7\u20130.\n\n===2015\u20132018===\n\nSince then, Zimbabwe are regularly organizing local competitions and events. They registered their biggest win in [[2015 African Olympic Qualifier (field hockey)|2015 African Olympic Qualifier]] by defeating Botswana by 19\u20130. [[Matthew Williams (cricketer)|Matthew Williams]] scored record 6 goals in the game, becoming first Zimbabwean ever to score more than 5 goals in a match. He emerged as highest scorer for Zimbabwe in the tournament by scoring 11 goals. In 2018, Zimbabwe played a 5 match test series against their arch rivals [[Namibia Hockey Union|Namibia]] and lost all the games. [[Tendayi Maredza]], who is currently the skipper of the team is regarded as one of the finest players in the African continent. Maredza was included in the International XI side that toured [[South Africa men's national field hockey team|South Africa]] in 2016\n\n===2018\u201319 Men's Hockey Series Open===\n\nThe [[2018\u201319 Men's Hockey Series Open#Bulawayo|2018\u201319 Men's Hockey Series Open]] was the first stage of the 2018\u201319 edition of the Hockey Series. It was held from June to December 2018. Zimbabwe participated and hosted the Bulawayo pool. Despite being the hosts, the Chevrons failed to qualify for the Olympic qualifiers and lost the spot to [[Egypt men's national field hockey team|Egypt]]. Tatenda Kanyangarara emerged as highest scorer for Zimbabwe.\n\n==Tournament history==\n===Summer Olympics===\n[[Field hockey at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]-12th Place\n\n===World Cup===\nNever Qualified\n\n===All-Africa Games===\n*[[1987 All-Africa Games|1987]] \u2013 {{sica}}\n*[[1991 All-Africa Games|1991]] \u2013 {{brca}}\n*[[1995 All-Africa Games|1995]] \u2013 4th Place\n*[[1999 All-Africa Games|1999]] \u2013 4th Place\n*[[2003 All-Africa Games|2003]] \u2013 5th Place\n\n===Hockey Africa Cup of Nations===\n* 1989 \u2013 4th Place\n* 1993 \u2013 4th Place\n* 1996 \u2013 4th Place\n* 2000 \u2013 {{brca}}\n\n===African Olympic Qualifiers===\n* [[2011 African Olympic Qualifier (field hockey)|2011]] \u2013 5th Place\n* [[2015 African Olympic Qualifier (field hockey)|2015]] \u2013 6th Place\n* [[2019 Men's African Olympic Qualifier|2019]] \u2013 4th Place\n\n==Current Squad==\n'''Head Coach:''' A Five\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Name\n!Caps\n!Goals\n!Role\n|-\n|1\n|Isheanesu Marima (GK) \n|4\n|0\n|Goal-Keeper\n|-\n|2\n|Takunda Chipumha\n|3\n|0\n|Defender\n|-\n|3\n|Gift Chomunorwa\n|3\n|0\n|Defender\n|-\n|4\n|'''Tendayi Maredza (c)'''\n|23\n|13\n|Forward\n|-\n|5\n|Edwin Tholanah\n|4\n|2\n|Forward\n|-\n|6\n|Kanyiwe Tafuma\n|4\n|1\n|Forward\n|-\n|7\n|Tapiwa Mushayakarara\n|4\n|0\n|Mid fielder\n|-\n|8\n|Pritchard Matambo\n|25\n|3\n|Defender\n|-\n|9\n|Luckson Sikisa\n|4\n|1\n|Mid fielder\n|-\n|10\n|Kudzanai Tembo\n|4\n|2\n|Mid fielder\n|-\n|11\n|Constantine Muchono\n|4\n|0\n|Defender\n|-\n|12\n|Kudzai Chimbetete (GK)\n|1\n|0\n|Goal-Keeper\n|-\n|13\n|Forbes Thindwa\n|4\n|2\n|Mid fielder\n|-\n|14\n|Tatenda Kanyangarara\n|3\n|3\n|Forward\n|}\n\n==Notable Former Players==\n* [[David Houghton (cricketer)|Dave Houghton]]\n* [[Lloyd Koch]]\n* [[John McPhun]]\n* [[Robert Ullyett]]\n* [[Collin Williams]]\n* [[Michael McKillop (cricketer)|Michael McKillop]]\n* [[Matthew Williams (cricketer)|Matthew Williams]]\n* Louis Mnyama\n\n==See also==\n*[[Zimbabwe women's national field hockey team]]\n*[[:Category:Rhodesian field hockey players|Rhodesian field hockey players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http