erborn (b. 1550)\n*[[1616]] &ndash; [[Miguel de Cervantes]], Spanish novelist, poet, and playwright (b. 1547)\n*[[1672]] &ndash; [[Georg Stiernhielm]], Swedish linguist and poet (b. 1598)\n*[[1699]] &ndash; [[Hans Erasmus A\u00dfmann]], German poet (b. 1646)\n*[[1758]] &ndash; [[Antoine de Jussieu]], French botanist and physician (b. 1686) \n*[[1778]] &ndash; [[James Hargreaves]], British inventor (b. 1720) \n*[[1806]] &ndash; [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]], French admiral (b. 1763)\n*[[1821]] &ndash; [[Gregory V of Constantinople]], Greek patriarch and saint (b. 1746)\n*[[1833]] &ndash; [[Richard Trevithick]], English engineer and explorer (b. 1771)\n*[[1850]] &ndash; [[Friedrich Robert Faehlmann]], Estonian philologist and physician (b. 1798)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Nicol\u00e1s Bravo]], Mexican general and politician, 11th [[President of Mexico]] (b. 1786)\n*[[1871]] &ndash; [[Mart\u00edn Carrera]], Mexican general and president (1855) (b. 1806)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://calderon.presidencia.gob.mx/mexico/gobernantes/mexico-1821-actualidad/martin-carrera/|publisher=Presidencia de la Republica de Mexico|title=MART\u00cdN CARRERA|language=Spanish|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[James P. Kirkwood]], Scottish-American engineer (b. 1807)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[\u00c9douard Lalo]], French violinist and composer (b. 1823)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Chaim Aronson]], Lithuanian businessman and author (b. 1825)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Kostas Krystallis]], Greek author and poet (b. 1868)\n*[[1896]] &ndash; [[Thomas Meik]], English engineer, founded [[Halcrow Group]] (b. 1812)\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]], Scottish-English merchant and politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (b. 1836)\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[Andr\u00e9 Caplet]], French composer and conductor (b. 1878)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Henry Lerolle]], French painter and art collector (b. 1848)\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Ferenc Oslay]], Hungarian-Slovene historian and author (b. 1883)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Henry Royce]], English engineer and businessman, co-founded [[Rolls-Royce Limited]] (b. 1863)\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Nikolaos Roussen]], Greek captain (b. 1913)\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Wilhelm Cauer]], German mathematician and academic (b. 1900)\n* 1945 &ndash; [[K\u00e4the Kollwitz]], German painter and sculptor (b. 1867)\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Lionel Atwill]], English-American actor (b. 1885)\n* 1946 &ndash; [[Harlan F. Stone]], American lawyer and jurist, 12th [[Chief Justice of the United States]] (b. 1872)\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Charles Middleton (actor)|Charles Middleton]], American actor (b. 1874)\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Charles Hamilton Houston]], American lawyer and academic (b. 1895)\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Horace Donisthorpe]], English myrmecologist and coleopterist (b. 1870)\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Walt Faulkner]], American race car driver (b. 1918)\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Stephen H. Sholes]], American record producer (b. 1911)\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Will Geer]], American actor (b. 1902)<ref>{{cite web |title=Will Geer \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff {{!}} IBDB |url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/will-geer-41913 |website=www.ibdb.com |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1980]] &ndash; [[Jane Froman]], American actress and singer (b. 1907)\n* 1980 &ndash; [[Fritz Strassmann]], German chemist and physicist (b. 1902)\n*[[1983]] &ndash; [[Earl Hines]], American pianist and bandleader (b. 1903)\n*[[1984]] &ndash; [[Ansel Adams]], American photographer and environmentalist (b. 1902)\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Paul Hugh Emmett]], American chemist and academic (b. 1900)\n* 1985 &ndash; [[Jacques Ferron]], Canadian physician and author (b. 1921)\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Mircea Eliade]], Romanian historian and author (b. 1907)\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Erika N\u00f5va]], Estonian architect (b. 1905)\n*[[1988]] &ndash; [[Grigori Kuzmin]], Russian-Estonian astronomer and academic (b. 1917)\n* 1988 &ndash; [[Irene Rich]], American actress (b. 1891)\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[Emilio G. Segr\u00e8]], Italian-American physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1905)\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Albert Salmi]], American actor (b. 1928)\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Richard Nixon]], American lieutenant, lawyer, and politician, 37th [[President of the United States]] (b. 1913)\n*[[1995]] &ndash; [[Jane Kenyon]], American poet and author (b. 1947)\n*[[1996]] &ndash; [[Erma Bombeck]], American journalist and author (b. 1927)\n* 1996 &ndash; [[Jug McSpaden]], American golfer and architect (b. 1908)\n*[[1998]] &ndash; [[Kitch Christie]], South African rugby player and coach (b. 1940)\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Chan Canasta]], Polish-English magician (b. 1920)\n* 1999 &ndash; [[Munir Ahmad Khan]], Pakistani nuclear engineer (b. 1926)\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[Linda Lovelace]], American porn actress and activist (b. 1949)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Felice Bryant]], American songwriter (b. 1925)\n* 2003 &ndash; [[James H. Critchfield]], American [[CIA]] officer (b. 1917)\n* 2003 &ndash; [[Martha Griffiths]], American lawyer, judge, and politician, 58th [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]] (b. 1912)\n* 2003 &ndash; [[Mike Larrabee]], American runner (b. 1933)\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Jason Dunham]], American soldier, [[Medal of Honor]] recipient (b. 1981)\n* 2004 &ndash; [[Pat Tillman]], American football player and soldier (b. 1976)\n*[[2005]] &ndash; [[Erika Fuchs]], German translator (b. 1906)\n* 2005 &ndash; [[Philip Morrison]], American physicist and academic (b. 1915)\n* 2005 &ndash; [[Eduardo Paolozzi]], Scottish sculptor and artist (b. 1924)\n*[[2006]] &ndash; [[Henriette Avram]], American computer scientist and academic (b. 1919)\n* 2006 &ndash; [[D'Iberville Fortier]], Canadian diplomat (b. 1926)\n* 2006 &ndash; [[Alida Valli]], Italian actress (b. 1921)\n*[[2007]] &ndash; [[Juanita Millender-McDonald]], American educator and politician (b. 1938)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Cameron Argetsinger]], American race car driver and lawyer (b. 1921)\n* 2008 &ndash; [[Ed Chynoweth]], Canadian businessman (b. 1941)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Jack Cardiff]], British cinematographer, director and photographer (b. 1914)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Richard Barrett (lawyer)|Richard Barrett]], American lawyer and activist (b. 1943)\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Hazel Dickens]], American singer-songwriter, bassist and guitarist (b. 1935)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[John Amabile (American football)|John Amabile]], American football player and coach (b. 1939)\n* 2012    &ndash; [[Bill Granger (author)|Bill Granger]], American author (b. 1941)\n* 2012    &ndash; [[Buzz Potamkin]], American director and producer (b. 1945)\n* 2012    &ndash; [[George Rathmann]], American chemist, biologist, and businessman (b. 1927)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Dave Gold]], American businessman, founded [[99 Cents Only Stores]] (b. 1932)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[George Stanley Gordon]], American businessman (b. 1926)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[Richie Havens]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. 1941)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[Lalgudi Jayaraman]], Indian violinist and composer (b. 1930)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[Mike Smith (footballer, born 1935)|Mike Smith]], English footballer (b. 1935)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[Robert Suderburg]], American pianist, composer, and conductor (b. 1936)\n* 2013 &ndash; [[J. S. Verma]], Indian judge, 27th [[Chief Justice of India]] (b. 1933)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Allen Jacobs]], American football player and coach (b. 1941)\n* 2014 &ndash; [[Jovan Krkobabi\u0107]], Serbian politician, [[Deputy Prime Minister of Serbia]] (b. 1930)\n* 2014 &ndash; [[Mohammad Naseem]], Pakistani-English activist (b. 1924)\n* 2014 &ndash; [[Werner Potzernheim]], German cyclist (b. 1927)\n* 2014 &ndash; [[Oswaldo Vigas]], Venezuelan painter (b. 1926)\n*[[2015]]  &ndash; [[Dick Balharry]], Scottish environmentalist and photographer (b. 1937)\n*  2015    &ndash; [[Gennadi Vengerov]], Belarusian-Russian actor (b. 1959)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Erin Moran]], American actress (b. 1960)\n*  2017    &ndash; [[Donna Williams|Donna Leanne Williams]], Australian writer, artist, activist (b. 1963)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.donnawilliams.net/2017/04/30/vale-polly-samuel-aka-donna-williams-1963-2017/|title=Vale Polly Samuel (aka 'Donna Williams') 1963-2017|date=2017-04-30|work=Polly's pages (aka 'Donna Williams')|access-date=2018-04-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n* Christian [[feast day]]:\n** [[Acepsimas of Hnaita]] and companions ([[Catholic Church]])\n** [[Arwald]]\n** [[Epipodius and Alexander]]\n** [[Hudson Stuck]] ([[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]])\n** [[John Muir]] ([[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]])\n** [[Opportuna of Montreuil]]\n** [[Pope Caius]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catholicreadings.org/catholic-quotes/saint-of-the-day-22-april-pope-saint-caius-i/|title=Saint of the Day - 22 April - Pope Saint Caius I|date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n** [[Pope Soter]]<ref>liturgialatina.blogspot.co.uk/2011/04/22nd-april-ss-soter-and-caius-popes-and.html</ref>\n** St [[Senorina]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=2492|title=St. Senorina - Saints & Angels - Catholic Online|first=Catholic|last=Online|website=Catholic Online}}</ref>\n** [[April 22 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n* [[Discovery Day]] (Brazil)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anydayguide.com/calendar/1924|title=Discovery Day in Brazil / April 22, 2018|last=AnydayGuide}}</ref>\n* [[Earth Day]] ([[International observance]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.earthday.org/earthday/|title=Earth Day 2018 - End Plastic Pollution}}</ref> and its related observance:\n** [[International Mother Earth Day]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/en/events/motherearthday/|title=International Mother Earth Day - 22 April|website=www.un.org}}</ref>\n* [[Holocaust Remembrance Day (Serbia)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.holocaustremembrance.com/country/serbia|title=Serbia - IHRA|website=www.holocaustremembrance.com}}</ref>\n* From 2018 onwards, a national day of commemoration for the murdered teenager [[Stephen Lawrence]] ([[United Kingdom]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43869377|title=Stephen Lawrence Day to be held annually|date=23 April 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/22 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=04|day=22}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/April_22 Today in Canadian History]\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:April]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBirths:Minor mistake.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/April_22"}
{"title_page": "Wylfa Nuclear Power Station", "text_new": "{{Infobox power station\n| name                    = Wylfa Nuclear Power Station\n| name_official           = \n| image                   = Outfall from Wylfa Power Station - geograph.org.uk - 668216.jpg\n| image_caption           = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|53.417|-4.483|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| country                 = [[Wales]], United Kingdom\n| location                = [[Anglesey]]\n| status                  = Closed\n| construction_began      = 1963\n| commissioned            = 1971\n| decommissioned          = 2015-2101\n| cost                    = \n| owner                   = [[Nuclear Decommissioning Authority]]\n| operator                = [[Magnox Ltd]]\n| ps_units_operational    = \n| ps_units_uc             = \n| ps_units_planned        = \n| ps_units_decommissioned = 2 x 490&nbsp;MW\n| np_reactor_type         = [[Magnox]]\n| np_reactor_supplier     = The Nuclear Power Group\n| ps_electrical_capacity  = \n| ps_electrical_cap_fac   = \n| ps_annual_generation    = \n| website                 = \n}}\n[[File:Wylfa nuclear power station, from above.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Wylfa just after closure]]\n'''Wylfa Nuclear Power Station''' ({{lang-cy|Atomfa'r Wylfa}}) is a former [[Magnox]] [[power station]] situated west of [[Cemaes Bay]] on the island of [[Anglesey]], off the northwestern coast of [[Wales]]. Construction of the two 490 MW nuclear reactors, known as \"Reactor 1\" and \"Reactor 2\", began in 1963. They became operational in 1971. Wylfa was located on the coast because seawater was used as a coolant.\n\nIn 2012, Reactor 2 was shut down. Three years later, Reactor 1 was switched off on 30 December 2015 so ending 44 years of operation at the site.\n\n'''Wylfa Newydd''' (literally New Wylfa) is a proposed new nuclear station on a site adjacent to the old plant. An application to build two [[advanced boiling water reactor]]s was submitted by [[Horizon Nuclear Power]] to the [[Office of Nuclear Regulation]] on 4 April 2017.\n\n==History==\nWylfa was the second nuclear power station to be built in [[Wales]] after [[Trawsfynydd nuclear power station|Trawsfynydd]] in 1959. Following the closure of Trawsfynydd in 1991, Wylfa became Wales' only nuclear power station.\n\nConstruction of Wylfa, which was undertaken by British Nuclear Design & Construction (BNDC), a consortium backed by [[English Electric]], [[Babcock & Wilcox Ltd]] and [[Taylor Woodrow Construction]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/country-profiles/countries-t-z/appendices/nuclear-development-in-the-united-kingdom.aspx|title=Nuclear Development in the United Kingdom -UK Nuclear Energy Development - World Nuclear Association|website=www.world-nuclear.org}}</ref> began in 1963. The reactors were supplied by The Nuclear Power Group (TNPG) and the turbines by [[English Electric]]. These were the largest and last Magnox-type reactors to be built in the UK. Wylfa was also the second British nuclear power station, following [[Oldbury nuclear power station|Oldbury]], to have a pre-stressed concrete pressure vessel instead of steel for easier construction and enhanced safety.\n\nWylfa's two 490&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW]] [[Magnox]] [[nuclear reactor]]s, \"Reactor 1\" and \"Reactor 2\" became operational in 1971.<ref name=plants>[http://www.industcards.com/nuclear-uk-sc-wl.htm Nuclear Power Plants in the UK - Scotland and Wales] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090719124719/http%3A//www.industcards.com/nuclear%2Duk%2Dsc%2Dwl.htm |date=19 July 2009 }}</ref> They typically supplied 23&nbsp;[[Gigawatt|GW]]&nbsp;[[hour|h]] of electricity daily when they were both in service. \n\nAlthough the original design output was 1,190&nbsp;MW, unexpected accelerated (\"breakaway\") corrosion of [[mild steel]] components of the gas circuit in hot [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] was detected even before the first reactor began operating. The channel gas outlet temperature, the temperature at which the CO<sub>2</sub> leaves the fuel channels in the reactor core, had to be reduced, initially dropping the power output to 840&nbsp;MW, which was later raised to 980&nbsp;MW as more experience accumulated. A considerable portion of the output, up to 255 MW, was consumed by the nearby [[Anglesey Aluminium]] smelting plant.<ref name=bbc-20090115>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/7829478.stm |title=Power deal threat to metal plant |work=BBC News |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe graphite cores each weigh {{convert|3800|tonne|LT|-2|lk=on}}; 6,156 vertical fuel channels contain over 49,248 natural uranium [[magnox (alloy)|magnox]]-clad fuel elements, hence the name magnox reactor.  A further 200 channels allow [[boron]] control rods to enter the reactor and control the nuclear reaction. The primary coolant in the reactors is [[carbon dioxide]] gas.\n\nThe power station is still managed by Magnox Ltd, formerly Magnox North, formerly British Nuclear Group, formerly Magnox Electric, formerly Nuclear Electric, formerly National Power, formerly the Central Electricity Generating Board (CEGB). The site is owned by the [[Nuclear Decommissioning Authority]] (NDA). Its purpose is to oversee the decommissioning and clean-up of the UK's civil nuclear legacy.\n\nDuring its operational life substantial works were needed to strengthen the reactors against deteriorating welds discovered in the safety review in April 2000.  Amid public controversy, Greenpeace issued an independent safety appraisal<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/taxonomy/term/454 Review of ageing processes and their influence on safety and performance of Wylfa nuclear power station] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203132717/http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/taxonomy/term/454 |date=3 December 2008 }}, Greenpeace</ref> commissioned a report from Large Associates, critical of the plant and its restart plans, but the permit to restart operation was given in August 2001.  In addition to welding weaknesses, radiolytic depletion of the graphite moderator blocks was still of concern and PAWB continue to campaign for early shut-down of the plant as well as against any nuclear replacement.\n\n===Closure and Decomissioning===\n\nOn 20 July 2006, the NDA announced that the station would be shut down in 2010 to enable the closure and decommissioning of the Magnox spent fuel reprocessing plant at [[Sellafield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/5198146.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=20 July 2006 |title= Wylfa definitely closing in 2010 |accessdate= 2007-12-10}}</ref> [[Springfields|Springfields Fuels Limited]] ended production of Magnox fuel elements in 2008 due to these plans.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Final shipment of new Magnox fuel|url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/ENF-Final_shipment_of_new_Magnox_fuel-1912114.html|website = www.world-nuclear-news.org|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  In 2010 the NDA announced an extension to 2012, beyond Wylfa's 40th anniversary as a generating power station in January 2011, due to schedule slippage at Sellafield which would allow Wylfa additional time before final defuelling.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sc=2057790 |title=Wylfa to continue generating until 2012 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=13 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305192914/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sc=2057790 |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = The Magnox life extension story - Nuclear Engineering International|url = http://www.neimagazine.com/features/featurethe-magnox-life-extension-story/|website = www.neimagazine.com|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  At this time, a strategy was also devised to maximise the generation from the remaining fuel stock given that new fuel could no longer be manufactured.  This required a change in the distribution of fuel within the reactors, as well as the closure of Reactor 2 in 2012 to allow this fuel to be transferred into Reactor 1.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Inter-reactor fuel transfer at Wylfa 1&2 - Nuclear Engineering International|url = http://www.neimagazine.com/features/featureinter-reactor-fuel-transfer-at-wylfa-12-4275091/|website = www.neimagazine.com|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  Reactor 2 ceased generating on 25 April 2012 at 19:02 BST,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-17840548|work=[[BBC News]]|date=26 April 2012|title=Nuclear workers offered retraining as Wylfa reactor shuts early|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref> allowing Reactor 1 to continue to operate.  A license extension to operate Reactor 1 until 31 December 2015 was granted in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-29433019|title=Wylfa nuclear plant given extension|date=30 September 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nReactor 1 was shut down on 30 December 2015. De-fuelling started in 2016. The whole site should be [[spent nuclear fuel]] free by late 2018. <ref name=wnn-20151231>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/WR-Worlds-last-operating-Magnox-reactor-closes-31121501.html |title=World's last operating Magnox reactor closes |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=31 December 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nDefuelling and removal of most buildings is expected to take until 2025, followed by a care and maintenance phase from 2025 to 2096.  Demolition of reactor buildings and final site clearance is planned for 2096 to 2101 <ref name=\"ndaDecomissioning\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nda.gov.uk/ukinventory/documents/Reports/upload/2010-UK-Radioactive-Waste-Inventory-Main-Report.pdf | title=The 2010 UK Radioactive Waste Inventory: Main Report | publisher=Nuclear Decommissioning Agency/Department of Energy & Climate Change | date=February 2011 | accessdate=22 May 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325081518/http://www.nda.gov.uk/ukinventory/documents/Reports/upload/2010-UK-Radioactive-Waste-Inventory-Main-Report.pdf | archivedate=25 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Future nuclear plant plans==\n[[File:Wylfa nuclear power station - geograph.org.uk - 1717137.jpg|thumb|Wylfa nuclear power station from Llanbadrig Point]]\nA second plant named Wylfa Newydd (previously referred to as Wylfa B<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/business/business-news/wylfa-b-re-named-wylfa-newydd-6308336|title=Wylfa B is re-named Wylfa Newydd by nuclear developer|work=Daily Post|date=15 November 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>) has been proposed. Wylfa Newydd's proposal has been the subject of local opposition, led by the group [[PAWB (People Against Wylfa-B)|People Against Wylfa B]] (PAWB<ref name=pawb>{{cite web | url= http://stop-wylfa.org |title= stop-wylfa.org}}</ref> \u2013 \"pawb\" is Welsh for \"everyone\"). In March 2006 the local council voted to extend the life of Wylfa A and to support the construction of Wylfa B, citing the potential loss of employment in the smelter works and nuclear station.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/doc.asp?cat=2080&doc=2749 | title= Council votes in favour of new power plant | work= [[Isle of Anglesey County Council]] | date= 3 March 2006 | accessdate= 2007-12-10 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235312/http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/doc.asp?cat=2080&doc=2749 | archivedate= 27 September 2007 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Horizon Nuclear Power]], originally an [[E.ON UK|E.ON]] and [[RWE]] joint venture, bought by Hitachi in 2012,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hitachi buys UK nuclear project from E.On and RWE|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20134735|date=30 April 2009|publisher=BBC}}</ref> announced in 2009 intentions to install about 3,000 MWe of new nuclear plant at Wylfa. Horizon is planning to build two [[advanced boiling water reactor]]s (ABWRs) at a site to the south of the existing Wylfa station.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/1803109/rwe-eon-edf-win-nuclear-auction |title=RWE/E.ON and EDF win nuclear auction |author=James Murray |publisher=BusinessGreen |date=30 April 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=horizon-faq>{{cite web |url=http://www.horizonnuclearpower.com/faq_wylfa.php |title=FAQs: WYLFA |publisher=Horizon Nuclear Power |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2010, the British government announced that Wylfa was one of the eight sites it considered suitable for future nuclear power stations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuclear power: Eight sites identified for future plants |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=18 October 2010 |date=18 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, three hundred [[anti-nuclear]] protesters took to the streets of Llangefni, against plans to build a new nuclear power station at Wylfa. The march was organised by organisations including Pobl Atal Wylfa B, Greenpeace and Cymdeithas yr Iaith, which are supporting farmer Richard Jones who is in dispute with Horizon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theonlinemail.co.uk/bangor-and-anglesey-news/local-bangor-and-anglesey-news/2012/01/25/hundreds-protest-against-nuclear-power-station-plans-66580-30188845/ |title=Hundreds protest against nuclear power station plans |author=Elgan Hearn |date=Jan 25, 2012  |work=Online Mail }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Horizon Nuclear Power|Horizon]] planned initial site work to start at Wylfa in 2015, with building work starting in 2018 and generation starting in the mid-2020s.<ref name=bbc-20131021>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-24601964 |title=Wylfa B nuclear power station: Housing concerns for workers |author=Chris Dearden |publisher=BBC |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\nThis timescale was delayed, and as of 2018 Hitachi planned to make the final investment decision in 2019.<ref name=wnn-20181022>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Hitachi-appoints-three-further-Wylfa-Newydd-partne |title=Hitachi appoints three further Wylfa Newydd partners |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=22 October 2018 |accessdate=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the 4 April 2017, Horizon submitted a Site Licence Application to the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.horizonnuclearpower.com/news-and-events/news/news-details/388|title=Horizon Nuclear Power|website=www.horizonnuclearpower.com}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-nuclear-horizon-idUKKBN1760VX|title=Hitachi unit applies for site licence for UK's Wylfa nuclear plant|date=4 April 2017|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\nThe scheme now includes a tunnel under the [[Menai Strait]] to carry the power cables to protect the conservation worth of the Strait and the [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-37495774|title=Wylfa Newydd: Power tunnel under Menai Strait to cost \u00a3100m|access-date=2 October 2016|date=30 September 2016|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2017, Horizon believes a consensus now of government and industry is that the Contract for Difference financing model used for [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]], involving fully private sector financing, will not used for subsequent nuclear plants, and is in discussions with government about alternative finance mechanisms.<ref name=ft-20171219>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/088c1dd6-e40e-11e7-97e2-916d4fbac0da |title=Britain's next nuclear plant eyes new funding models |last=Ward |first=Andrew |newspaper=Financial Times |date=19 December 2017 |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe UK government intends to invest \u00a35 billion in the new power station. Previously, government policy had been not to invest directly in new nuclear projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaughan |first1=Adam |title=UK takes \u00a35bn stake in Welsh nuclear power station in policy U-turn |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/jun/04/uk-takes-5bn-stake-in-welsh-nuclear-power-station-in-policy-u-turn |accessdate=4 June 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nHorizon Nuclear Power submitted a Development Consent Order application for the Wylfa Newydd project to the [[Planning Inspectorate]] on 1 June 2018. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Edgar |first1=Laura |title=DCO application submitted for Wylfa Newydd |url=https://www.theplanner.co.uk/news/dco-application-submitted-for-wylfa-newydd |website=The Planner |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Possible cancellation of construction===\nIn January 2019, it was reported that the nuclear plant\u2019s funding was questionable, after \u00a32 billion had been spent on the project. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/10/uk-nuclear-plant-hitachi-wylfa-anglesey|title=UK\u2019s nuclear plans in doubt after report Welsh plant may be axed|first=Adam|last=Vaughan|date=10 December 2018|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> The reports noted that a dispute between the proposed plant\u2019s builder [[Hitachi]] and the UK government over funding had thrown the future construction into doubt, and that an upcoming meeting later in the month would be the location of an announcement regarding the plant\u2019s future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/01/11/hitachi-set-walk-away-wylfa-nuclear-power-plant/|title=Hitachi weighs pulling out of Welsh nuclear power plant|first=Chris|last=Johnston|date=11 January 2019|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2019, Hitachi announced that it would \"suspend\" work on the Wylfa project. Duncan Hawthorne, chief executive of Horizon Nuclear Power, said: \"...we will take steps to reduce our presence but keep the option to resume development in future\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/hitachi-to-suspend-work-on-20bn-nuclear-reactor-in-wales-11609379 |title=Hitachi to suspend work on \u00a320bn nuclear reactor in Wales |work=Sky News |date=17 January 2019}}</ref> The UK government had been expected to grant a development consent order in a move to restart the project,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=David |title=Wylfa Newydd / UK Delays Decision On Planning Permission |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/uk-delays-decision-on-planning-permission-10-4-2019 |work=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> but subsequently deferred the decision deadline until 30 September 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=David |title=Wylfa Newydd / Decision On UK Nuclear Plant Put Back Until September |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/decision-on-uk-nuclear-plant-put-back-until-september-4-4-2020 |work=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Wales|Energy|Nuclear technology}}}}\n*[[Nuclear power in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Anti-nuclear movement in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Economics of new nuclear power plants]]\n*[[Proposed nuclear power stations in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wylfa nuclear power station}}\n*[http://www.magnoxsites.com/site/wylfa/ Wylfa | Magnox Sites]\n*[http://www.anglesey-today.com/wylfa.html Wylfa Power Station]\n*[http://www.nda.gov.uk/ NDA (UK Nuclear Decommissioning Authority)]\n*[http://econtent.unm.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/nuceng&CISOPTR=41&CISOBOX=1&REC=5 Wylfa], Nuclear Engineering International wall chart, 1965\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140513011047/http://www.archivesnetworkwales.info/cgi-bin/anw/fulldesc_nofr?inst_id=27&coll_id=76901 Information on PAWB]\n*[http://www.stop-wylfa.org/ PAWB Website]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/7908934.stm Inside Wylfa. Feb 2009 (2m:21s video)]\n\n{{British nuclear power plants}}\n{{Energy in Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Anglesey]]\n[[Category:Nuclear power stations in Wales]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure completed in 1971]]\n[[Category:Llanbadrig]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox power station\n| name                    = Wylfa Nuclear Power Station\n| name_official           = \n| image                   = Outfall from Wylfa Power Station - geograph.org.uk - 668216.jpg\n| image_caption           = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|53.417|-4.483|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| country                 = [[Wales]], United Kingdom\n| location                = [[Anglesey]]\n| status                  = Closed\n| construction_began      = 1963\n| commissioned            = 1971\n| decommissioned          = 2015\n| cost                    = \n| owner                   = [[Nuclear Decommissioning Authority]]\n| operator                = [[Magnox Ltd]]\n| ps_units_operational    = \n| ps_units_uc             = \n| ps_units_planned        = \n| ps_units_decommissioned = 2 x 490&nbsp;MW\n| np_reactor_type         = [[Magnox]]\n| np_reactor_supplier     = The Nuclear Power Group\n| ps_electrical_capacity  = \n| ps_electrical_cap_fac   = \n| ps_annual_generation    = \n| website                 = \n}}\n[[File:Wylfa nuclear power station, from above.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Wylfa just after closure]]\n'''Wylfa Nuclear Power Station''' ({{lang-cy|Atomfa'r Wylfa}}) is a former [[Magnox]] [[power station]] situated west of [[Cemaes Bay]] on the island of [[Anglesey]], off the northwestern coast of [[Wales]]. Construction of the two 490 MW nuclear reactors, known as \"Reactor 1\" and \"Reactor 2\", began in 1963. They became operational in 1971. Wylfa was located on the coast because seawater was used as a coolant.\n\nIn 2012, Reactor 2 was shut down. Three years later, Reactor 1 was switched off on 30 December 2015 so ending 44 years of operation at the site.\n\n'''Wylfa Newydd''' (literally New Wylfa) is a proposed new nuclear station on a site adjacent to the old plant. An application to build two [[advanced boiling water reactor]]s was submitted by [[Horizon Nuclear Power]] to the [[Office of Nuclear Regulation]] on 4 April 2017.\n\n==History==\nWylfa was the second nuclear power station to be built in [[Wales]] after [[Trawsfynydd nuclear power station|Trawsfynydd]] in 1959. Following the closure of Trawsfynydd in 1991, Wylfa became Wales' only nuclear power station.\n\nConstruction of Wylfa, which was undertaken by British Nuclear Design & Construction (BNDC), a consortium backed by [[English Electric]], [[Babcock & Wilcox Ltd]] and [[Taylor Woodrow Construction]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/country-profiles/countries-t-z/appendices/nuclear-development-in-the-united-kingdom.aspx|title=Nuclear Development in the United Kingdom -UK Nuclear Energy Development - World Nuclear Association|website=www.world-nuclear.org}}</ref> began in 1963. The reactors were supplied by The Nuclear Power Group (TNPG) and the turbines by [[English Electric]]. These were the largest and last Magnox-type reactors to be built in the UK. Wylfa was also the second British nuclear power station, following [[Oldbury nuclear power station|Oldbury]], to have a pre-stressed concrete pressure vessel instead of steel for easier construction and enhanced safety.\n\nWylfa's two 490&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW]] [[Magnox]] [[nuclear reactor]]s, \"Reactor 1\" and \"Reactor 2\" became operational in 1971.<ref name=plants>[http://www.industcards.com/nuclear-uk-sc-wl.htm Nuclear Power Plants in the UK - Scotland and Wales] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090719124719/http%3A//www.industcards.com/nuclear%2Duk%2Dsc%2Dwl.htm |date=19 July 2009 }}</ref> They typically supplied 23&nbsp;[[Gigawatt|GW]]&nbsp;[[hour|h]] of electricity daily when they were both in service. \n\nAlthough the original design output was 1,190&nbsp;MW, unexpected accelerated (\"breakaway\") corrosion of [[mild steel]] components of the gas circuit in hot [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] was detected even before the first reactor began operating. The channel gas outlet temperature, the temperature at which the CO<sub>2</sub> leaves the fuel channels in the reactor core, had to be reduced, initially dropping the power output to 840&nbsp;MW, which was later raised to 980&nbsp;MW as more experience accumulated. A considerable portion of the output, up to 255 MW, was consumed by the nearby [[Anglesey Aluminium]] smelting plant.<ref name=bbc-20090115>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/7829478.stm |title=Power deal threat to metal plant |work=BBC News |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe graphite cores each weigh {{convert|3800|tonne|LT|-2|lk=on}}; 6,156 vertical fuel channels contain over 49,248 natural uranium [[magnox (alloy)|magnox]]-clad fuel elements, hence the name magnox reactor.  A further 200 channels allow [[boron]] control rods to enter the reactor and control the nuclear reaction. The primary coolant in the reactors is [[carbon dioxide]] gas.\n\nThe power station is still managed by Magnox Ltd, formerly Magnox North, formerly British Nuclear Group, formerly Magnox Electric, formerly Nuclear Electric, formerly National Power, formerly the Central Electricity Generating Board (CEGB). The site is owned by the [[Nuclear Decommissioning Authority]] (NDA). Its purpose is to oversee the decommissioning and clean-up of the UK's civil nuclear legacy.\n\nDuring its operational life substantial works were needed to strengthen the reactors against deteriorating welds discovered in the safety review in April 2000.  Amid public controversy, Greenpeace issued an independent safety appraisal<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/taxonomy/term/454 Review of ageing processes and their influence on safety and performance of Wylfa nuclear power station] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203132717/http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/taxonomy/term/454 |date=3 December 2008 }}, Greenpeace</ref> commissioned a report from Large Associates, critical of the plant and its restart plans, but the permit to restart operation was given in August 2001.  In addition to welding weaknesses, radiolytic depletion of the graphite moderator blocks was still of concern and PAWB continue to campaign for early shut-down of the plant as well as against any nuclear replacement.\n\n===Closure and Decomissioning===\n\nOn 20 July 2006, the NDA announced that the station would be shut down in 2010 to enable the closure and decommissioning of the Magnox spent fuel reprocessing plant at [[Sellafield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/5198146.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=20 July 2006 |title= Wylfa definitely closing in 2010 |accessdate= 2007-12-10}}</ref> [[Springfields|Springfields Fuels Limited]] ended production of Magnox fuel elements in 2008 due to these plans.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Final shipment of new Magnox fuel|url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/ENF-Final_shipment_of_new_Magnox_fuel-1912114.html|website = www.world-nuclear-news.org|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  In 2010 the NDA announced an extension to 2012, beyond Wylfa's 40th anniversary as a generating power station in January 2011, due to schedule slippage at Sellafield which would allow Wylfa additional time before final defuelling.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sc=2057790 |title=Wylfa to continue generating until 2012 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=13 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305192914/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sc=2057790 |archivedate=5 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = The Magnox life extension story - Nuclear Engineering International|url = http://www.neimagazine.com/features/featurethe-magnox-life-extension-story/|website = www.neimagazine.com|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  At this time, a strategy was also devised to maximise the generation from the remaining fuel stock given that new fuel could no longer be manufactured.  This required a change in the distribution of fuel within the reactors, as well as the closure of Reactor 2 in 2012 to allow this fuel to be transferred into Reactor 1.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Inter-reactor fuel transfer at Wylfa 1&2 - Nuclear Engineering International|url = http://www.neimagazine.com/features/featureinter-reactor-fuel-transfer-at-wylfa-12-4275091/|website = www.neimagazine.com|accessdate = 2015-07-04}}</ref>  Reactor 2 ceased generating on 25 April 2012 at 19:02 BST,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-17840548|work=[[BBC News]]|date=26 April 2012|title=Nuclear workers offered retraining as Wylfa reactor shuts early|accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref> allowing Reactor 1 to continue to operate.  A license extension to operate Reactor 1 until 31 December 2015 was granted in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-29433019|title=Wylfa nuclear plant given extension|date=30 September 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nReactor 1 was shut down on 30 December 2015. De-fuelling started in 2016. The whole site should be [[spent nuclear fuel]] free by late 2018. <ref name=wnn-20151231>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/WR-Worlds-last-operating-Magnox-reactor-closes-31121501.html |title=World's last operating Magnox reactor closes |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=31 December 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nDefuelling and removal of most buildings is expected to take until 2025, followed by a care and maintenance phase from 2025 to 2096.  Demolition of reactor buildings and final site clearance is planned for 2096 to 2101 <ref name=\"ndaDecomissioning\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nda.gov.uk/ukinventory/documents/Reports/upload/2010-UK-Radioactive-Waste-Inventory-Main-Report.pdf | title=The 2010 UK Radioactive Waste Inventory: Main Report | publisher=Nuclear Decommissioning Agency/Department of Energy & Climate Change | date=February 2011 | accessdate=22 May 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325081518/http://www.nda.gov.uk/ukinventory/documents/Reports/upload/2010-UK-Radioactive-Waste-Inventory-Main-Report.pdf | archivedate=25 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Future nuclear plant plans==\n[[File:Wylfa nuclear power station - geograph.org.uk - 1717137.jpg|thumb|Wylfa nuclear power station from Llanbadrig Point]]\nA second plant named Wylfa Newydd (previously referred to as Wylfa B<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/business/business-news/wylfa-b-re-named-wylfa-newydd-6308336|title=Wylfa B is re-named Wylfa Newydd by nuclear developer|work=Daily Post|date=15 November 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>) has been proposed. Wylfa Newydd's proposal has been the subject of local opposition, led by the group [[PAWB (People Against Wylfa-B)|People Against Wylfa B]] (PAWB<ref name=pawb>{{cite web | url= http://stop-wylfa.org |title= stop-wylfa.org}}</ref> \u2013 \"pawb\" is Welsh for \"everyone\"). In March 2006 the local council voted to extend the life of Wylfa A and to support the construction of Wylfa B, citing the potential loss of employment in the smelter works and nuclear station.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/doc.asp?cat=2080&doc=2749 | title= Council votes in favour of new power plant | work= [[Isle of Anglesey County Council]] | date= 3 March 2006 | accessdate= 2007-12-10 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235312/http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/doc.asp?cat=2080&doc=2749 | archivedate= 27 September 2007 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Horizon Nuclear Power]], originally an [[E.ON UK|E.ON]] and [[RWE]] joint venture, bought by Hitachi in 2012,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hitachi buys UK nuclear project from E.On and RWE|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20134735|date=30 April 2009|publisher=BBC}}</ref> announced in 2009 intentions to install about 3,000 MWe of new nuclear plant at Wylfa. Horizon is planning to build two [[advanced boiling water reactor]]s (ABWRs) at a site to the south of the existing Wylfa station.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/1803109/rwe-eon-edf-win-nuclear-auction |title=RWE/E.ON and EDF win nuclear auction |author=James Murray |publisher=BusinessGreen |date=30 April 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=horizon-faq>{{cite web |url=http://www.horizonnuclearpower.com/faq_wylfa.php |title=FAQs: WYLFA |publisher=Horizon Nuclear Power |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2010, the British government announced that Wylfa was one of the eight sites it considered suitable for future nuclear power stations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuclear power: Eight sites identified for future plants |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=18 October 2010 |date=18 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, three hundred [[anti-nuclear]] protesters took to the streets of Llangefni, against plans to build a new nuclear power station at Wylfa. The march was organised by organisations including Pobl Atal Wylfa B, Greenpeace and Cymdeithas yr Iaith, which are supporting farmer Richard Jones who is in dispute with Horizon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theonlinemail.co.uk/bangor-and-anglesey-news/local-bangor-and-anglesey-news/2012/01/25/hundreds-protest-against-nuclear-power-station-plans-66580-30188845/ |title=Hundreds protest against nuclear power station plans |author=Elgan Hearn |date=Jan 25, 2012  |work=Online Mail }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Horizon Nuclear Power|Horizon]] planned initial site work to start at Wylfa in 2015, with building work starting in 2018 and generation starting in the mid-2020s.<ref name=bbc-20131021>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-24601964 |title=Wylfa B nuclear power station: Housing concerns for workers |author=Chris Dearden |publisher=BBC |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\nThis timescale was delayed, and as of 2018 Hitachi planned to make the final investment decision in 2019.<ref name=wnn-20181022>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Hitachi-appoints-three-further-Wylfa-Newydd-partne |title=Hitachi appoints three further Wylfa Newydd partners |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=22 October 2018 |accessdate=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the 4 April 2017, Horizon submitted a Site Licence Application to the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.horizonnuclearpower.com/news-and-events/news/news-details/388|title=Horizon Nuclear Power|website=www.horizonnuclearpower.com}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-nuclear-horizon-idUKKBN1760VX|title=Hitachi unit applies for site licence for UK's Wylfa nuclear plant|date=4 April 2017|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\nThe scheme now includes a tunnel under the [[Menai Strait]] to carry the power cables to protect the conservation worth of the Strait and the [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-37495774|title=Wylfa Newydd: Power tunnel under Menai Strait to cost \u00a3100m|access-date=2 October 2016|date=30 September 2016|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2017, Horizon believes a consensus now of government and industry is that the Contract for Difference financing model used for [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]], involving fully private sector financing, will not used for subsequent nuclear plants, and is in discussions with government about alternative finance mechanisms.<ref name=ft-20171219>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/088c1dd6-e40e-11e7-97e2-916d4fbac0da |title=Britain's next nuclear plant eyes new funding models |last=Ward |first=Andrew |newspaper=Financial Times |date=19 December 2017 |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe UK government intends to invest \u00a35 billion in the new power station. Previously, government policy had been not to invest directly in new nuclear projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaughan |first1=Adam |title=UK takes \u00a35bn stake in Welsh nuclear power station in policy U-turn |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/jun/04/uk-takes-5bn-stake-in-welsh-nuclear-power-station-in-policy-u-turn |accessdate=4 June 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nHorizon Nuclear Power submitted a Development Consent Order application for the Wylfa Newydd project to the [[Planning Inspectorate]] on 1 June 2018. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Edgar |first1=Laura |title=DCO application submitted for Wylfa Newydd |url=https://www.theplanner.co.uk/news/dco-application-submitted-for-wylfa-newydd |website=The Planner |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Possible cancellation of construction===\nIn January 2019, it was reported that the nuclear plant\u2019s funding was questionable, after \u00a32 billion had been spent on the project. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/10/uk-nuclear-plant-hitachi-wylfa-anglesey|title=UK\u2019s nuclear plans in doubt after report Welsh plant may be axed|first=Adam|last=Vaughan|date=10 December 2018|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> The reports noted that a dispute between the proposed plant\u2019s builder [[Hitachi]] and the UK government over funding had thrown the future construction into doubt, and that an upcoming meeting later in the month would be the location of an announcement regarding the plant\u2019s future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/01/11/hitachi-set-walk-away-wylfa-nuclear-power-plant/|title=Hitachi weighs pulling out of Welsh nuclear power plant|first=Chris|last=Johnston|date=11 January 2019|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2019, Hitachi announced that it would \"suspend\" work on the Wylfa project. Duncan Hawthorne, chief executive of Horizon Nuclear Power, said: \"...we will take steps to reduce our presence but keep the option to resume development in future\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/hitachi-to-suspend-work-on-20bn-nuclear-reactor-in-wales-11609379 |title=Hitachi to suspend work on \u00a320bn nuclear reactor in Wales |work=Sky News |date=17 January 2019}}</ref> The UK government had been expected to grant a development consent order in a move to restart the project,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=David |title=Wylfa Newydd / UK Delays Decision On Planning Permission |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/uk-delays-decision-on-planning-permission-10-4-2019 |work=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> but subsequently deferred the decision deadline until 30 September 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=David |title=Wylfa Newydd / Decision On UK Nuclear Plant Put Back Until September |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/decision-on-uk-nuclear-plant-put-back-until-september-4-4-2020 |work=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Wales|Energy|Nuclear technology}}}}\n*[[Nuclear power in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Anti-nuclear movement in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Economics of new nuclear power plants]]\n*[[Proposed nuclear power stations in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wylfa nuclear power station}}\n*[http://www.magnoxsites.com/site/wylfa/ Wylfa | Magnox Sites]\n*[http://www.anglesey-today.com/wylfa.html Wylfa Power Station]\n*[http://www.nda.gov.uk/ NDA (UK Nuclear Decommissioning Authority)]\n*[http://econtent.unm.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/nuceng&CISOPTR=41&CISOBOX=1&REC=5 Wylfa], Nuclear Engineering International wall chart, 