]\n| {{n/a|Miss Diversity }}\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[Ayesha Gilani]]<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20151127231351/http://sapnamagazine.com/2010/miss-pakistan-world-ayesha-gilani/</ref><ref>https://www.khaleejtimes.com/citytimes/-i-was-born-ready</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southasianoutlook.com/issues/2009/july/ayesha_gilani_miss_pakistan_world_2009.html|title=South Asian Outlook Ayesha Gilani Miss Pakistan World 2009|website=www.southasianoutlook.com}}</ref>  \n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| {{n/a|Unplaced in [[Miss Earth]] & Beauty of the World, Miss Tourism Queen International}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[Natasha Paracha]]<ref>https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/oops-pak-beauty-condones-blasts/cid/515859</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/19/nyregion/19bigcity.html|title=Pakistan May Not Be Ready for Its Beauty Queen|first=Susan|last=Dominus|date=18 December 2008|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| {{n/a| Withdrew from [[Miss Earth]] and was replaced by Nosheen Idrees and did not compete in international pageants}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[Mahleej Sarkari]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071215022448/http://www.indiaprwire.com/pressrelease/entertainment/200708073974.htm]</ref>\n| [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Baluchistan]]\n| {{n/a| Miss Tourism Queen International}}\n|-\n| 2006\n| Sehr Mahmood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/urdu/regional/story/2006/11/061123_beauty_contest_sq.shtml/|title=BBCUrdu.com|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n| [[Sindh (Pakistan)|Sindh]]\n| {{n/a|Unplaced in the [[Miss Earth]], Miss Elegant position won in Queen of the World}}\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Naomi Zaman]]\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| {{n/a|Debut in [[Miss Earth]] & winner of Miss Dance Queen in Miss Tourism Queen International}}\n|-\n| 2004\n| Batool Cheema\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| {{n/a|Sent to Queen of the World 2009 and Miss Friendship 2009}}\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[Zehra Sheerazi]]\n| [[Sindh (Pakistan)|Sindh]]\n| [[Ottawa]]\n| {{n/a|Sent to World Miss University 2013}}\n|}\n\n===Representatives to Miss Earth===\nThe first representative to [[Miss Earth]] was [[Naomi Zaman]] in 2005 and since then there have been two years where Pakistan did not participate, 2007 & 2013. However, the winner of 2013 [[Shanzay Hayat]] represented Pakistan in the Miss Earth 2014 pageant held in Manila, Philippines on 29 November 2014. In 2008 [[Natasha Paracha]], Miss Pakistan World 2008 was replaced by runner up Nosheen Idrees.\n\n;Color keys\n{{plainlist|\n* {{color box|gold}} A year wherein the Pakistan earned a crown(s)\n* {{color box|#FFFF66}} A year wherein the Pakistan placed as a runner-up(s)\n* {{color box|#FFFACD}} A year wherein the Pakistan placed in the top 5, top 10, top 15, or as a semifinalist(s)\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Representative !! City, Province !! Ranking !! Special Awards\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2017|2017]]\n| [[Ramina Ashfaque]] \n| [[Sindh (Pakistan)|Sindh]]\n| Unplaced\n| Unplaced\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2016|2016]]\n| [[Anzhelika Tahir]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/arts-culture/2016/10/pakistani-girl-from-sheikhupura-bags-gold-medal-in-miss-earth-2016/|title=Pakistani girl wins gold at beauty pageant - Samaa TV|website=www.samaa.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/local-news/2016/10/19/ten-miss-earth-candidates-visit-iligan-ciy-504459|title=Ten Miss Earth candidates visit Iligan Ciy|first=Richel V.|last=Umel|date=19 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abplive.in/lifestyle/check-out-these-pakistani-beauty-queens-who-made-headlines-380467|title=Pakistani Beauty Qeens Who've Shed The Tag Of Being Conservative|first=ABP News|last=Bureau|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/world/2016/05/11/meet-anzhelika-tahir-pakistans-miss-world-2016|title=Meet Anzhelika Tahir, Pakistan's Miss World 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| {{gold01}} Talent Competition\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2014|2014]]\n| [[Shanzay Hayat]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beautypageantnews.com/shanzay-hayat-crowned-miss-pakistan-world-2013/|title=Shanzay Hayat Crowned Miss Pakistan World 2013 - Beauty Pageant News|date=1 September 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n| [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| Unplaced\n| {{gold01}} Talent Competition\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2012|2012]]\n| [[Zanib Naveed]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/video/bold-brave-answers-miss-pakistan-000000867.html|title=Bold and brave answers from Miss Pakistan Earth|publisher=}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| {{silver02}} Trivia Challenge<br> Award for press favorite <br>Miss SMDC\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2011|2011]]\n| [[Sanober Hussain]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/Hasleen-Kaur-at-Miss-Earth-2011/eventshow/11486607.cms|title=Hasleen Kaur with Miss Pakistan at Miss Earth in Manila, Philippines - BeautyPageants|website=Femina Miss India}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| Miss Friendship\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2009|2009]]\n| [[Ayesha Gilani]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashioncentral.pk/people-parties/events/festivals/story-350-miss-earth-pakistan-2009/|title=Miss Earth Pakistan 2009|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"missosology.org\">{{cite web|url=http://missosology.org/opinion/7077-focus-pakistans-participation-major-pageants/|title=IN FOCUS :: Pakistan's participation at major pageants - Missosology|last=Missosology|date=8 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| Top 15 Talent Finals\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2008|2008]]\n| Nosheen Idrees<ref name=\"missosology.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/130482/lifestyle/quake-worries-pakistan-s-miss-earth-candidate/|title=Quake worries Pakistan's Miss Earth candidate|website=GMA News Online}}</ref>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| None\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2006|2006]]\n| Sehr Mahmood<ref name=\"missosology.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southasianoutlook.com/issues/2007/june/celebrating_women_sehr_mahmood.html|title=South Asian Outlook - An Independent Monthly|first=Suresh Jaura, 33 Lafferty Street, Toronto, ONT M9C 5B5|last=CANADA|website=southasianoutlook.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041140/http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176 |archivedate=2014-11-29 }}</ref>\n| [[Sindh (Pakistan)|Sindh]]\n| Unplaced\n| None\n|-\n| [[Miss Earth 2005|2005]]\n| [[Naomi Zaman]]<ref name=\"missosology.org\"/>\n| [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| Unplaced\n| None\n|}\n\n==Controversy==\n===2006===\nIn 2006, one of the runner ups of Miss Pakistan World was sent to China to represent Pakistan in Miss Bikini of the Universe. That caused a stir<ref>https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/row-over-bikini-contestant-rages-1.255267</ref> in Pakistan.<ref>https://www.theasiantoday.com/index.php/2006/12/06/crowning-glory-for-miss-pakistan-beauty-pageants/</ref> However, Pakistan got its title of Best in Media<ref>https://www.houstonpress.com/news/bikini-revolution-6544639</ref> in the year 2006.<ref>http://old.paktribune.com/news/Pakistans-first-Miss-Bikini!-153100.html/?page=3</ref> The president of Miss Pakistan World, [[Sonia Ahmed]]<ref>https://www.financialexpress.com/archive/expat-pakistani-beauties-launch-bikini-rebellion/186675/</ref> defended the pageant and the titleholder<ref>https://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-a-rewarding-2006-for-pak-beauties-1065796</ref> and said that the contest will continue no matter what happened. \n\n===2008-2009===\nThe pageant has been criticised by Pakistani [[feminist]] [[Amna Buttar]] of the Asian-American Network Against Abuse of Human Rights, who wrote in an email to the ''[[New York Times]]'': <blockquote>\"In Pakistan, we are trying to get basic rights for women: right to marry, right to divorce, equal opportunity for job and education, and issues like Miss Pakistan create problems for this movement. An average Pakistani young woman does not want to wear a [[bikini]]<ref>https://gulfnews.com/news/asia/pakistan/row-over-bikini-contestant-rages-1.255267</ref> in public, and for her it is important to have equal opportunity and all focus should be on that, and not on a pageant where only the elite can participate.\"<ref name=\"NYT\"/></blockquote> [[Sonia Ahmed]] President of Miss Pakistan World defended<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southasianpost.com/article/4747-beauty-aims-fight-beasts-pakistan.html|title=Beauty aims to fight the beasts of Pakistan {{!}} South Asian Post {{!}} Indo Canadian newspaper - Vancouver, Surrey, Calgary, Toronto, Brampton, Edmonton, Winnipeg, Montreal|website=www.southasianpost.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> the event as a movement to express one's rights and freedom to do as one wishes.\n\nIn 2008, Miss Pakistan World landed in yet another controversy<ref>http://www.rediff.com/news/2008/apr/16look.htm</ref> and that was pertaining to the President of Pakistan<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/I-want-to-date-Mush-the-hunk/articleshow/2957969.cms</ref>, [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref>https://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-i-fell-in-love-with-musharraf-miss-pakistan-world-1160695</ref> The current Miss Pakistan World<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/india/musharraf-is-a-hunk-says-miss-pakistan-world-287413.html</ref> had expressed her desire<ref>http://www.sify.com/news/i-fell-in-love-with-musharraf-miss-pakistan-world-news-international-jegq0xbjjdgsi.html</ref> to date the President and confessed that she was in love<ref>https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/news/world/miss-pakistan-thinks-musharraf-is-a-hunk/articleshow/15802953.cms</ref> with the President.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/19/nyregion/19bigcity.html</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, the reigning Miss Pakistan World, Natasha Paracha<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/335008/</ref> used the word \"condone<ref>https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/oops-pak-beauty-condones-blasts/cid/515859</ref>\" instead of condemn<ref>https://southasia.typepad.com/south_asia_daily/2008/12/miss-pakistan-condones-mumbai-attacks-while-condemning-them-.html</ref> for the terrorist attacks on Mumbai. This caused the Indian community around the world to react.<ref>https://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-miss-pakistan-minces-her-words-condones-2611-1215341</ref>\n\n===2010===\nIn 2010 the pageant also fell into some controversy when it was held in the month of [[Ramadan]] as well as when the floods affected Pakistan 3 weeks prior to the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bu.edu/today/node/11438|title=Beauty Pageant Rookie Wins Crown - BU Today - Boston University|publisher=|access-date=16 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100904033347/http://www.bu.edu/today/node/11438|archive-date=4 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Toronto Star\">[[Toronto Star]], [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/850312--pakistani-beauty-pageant-to-go-ahead The flood in Pakistan will not stop the pageant in Toronto], Published On Thu 19 August 2010</ref><ref name=\"Globe and Mail\">Globe and Mail, ''[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/organizers-criticized-for-running-pakistani-pageant-in-wake-of-flood-disaster/article1679280/]'', Published on Thursday, 19 August 2010 10:30PM EDT</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">Alia Waheed, [[The Guardian]], \"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/aug/19/pakistan-anger-beauty-contest-floods Miss Pakistan World pageant's timing causes dismay: Demands for Toronto beauty contest to be called off in light of humanitarian crisis brought by flooding in Pakistan]\", Thursday 19 August 2010 18.16 BST</ref>\n\n===2012===\nMost contestants<ref>http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10818312 New Zealand Herald</ref> who participated from around the world<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/14881538.Scottish_model_Madiha_Iqbal_to_compete_in_Miss_World_Pakistan_event_in_Canada/|title=Scottish model Madiha Iqbal to compete in Miss World Pakistan event in Canada|website=Asian Image}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/delhi-times/Miss-Pakistan-via-Canada/articleshow/1986409.cms|title=Miss Pakistan, via Canada - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref> were highlighted during the pageant<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobalindian.co.nz/miss-pakistan-world-2012/|title=New Zealander finalist at Miss Pakistan World title - The Global Indian|publisher=}}</ref> as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asianexpress.co.uk/2016/11/canadas-crown-aberdeen-beauty-queen-to-compete-in-miss-pakistan/|title=Canada's crown? Aberdeen beauty queen to compete in Miss Pakistan|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://beauty.msn.co.nz/beautynews/latestnews/8496325/aucklander-up-for-miss-pakistan-crown Msn</ref> At a time when [[Pervez Musharraf]] was facing criticism from various political parties in Pakistan, one Miss Pakistan World confessed that she loved the president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-i-fell-in-love-with-musharraf-miss-pakistan-world-1160695|title=I fell in love with Musharraf: Miss Pakistan World - Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=21 April 2008|publisher=}}</ref> \nDuring the Mumbai Attacks, Miss Pakistan World<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-pakistan-s-image-soiled-after-mumbai-attacks-beauty-queen-1214422|title=Pakistan's image soiled after Mumbai attacks: Beauty queen - Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=16 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref> winners spoke about the incident and gave statements regarding the India Pakistan tension. During a CNN interview, Miss Pakistan World [[Natasha Paracha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-miss-pakistan-minces-her-words-condones-2611-1215341|title=Miss Pakistan minces her words, 'condones' 26/11 - Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=19 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref> used the word \"condone\" instead of \"condemn\" and it rolled on to become a huge controversy which dismayed many Indians.\n\n===2013-2019===\n\nIn 2016, [[Anzhelika Tahir]]<ref>https://www.parhlo.com/8-amazing-things-you-didnt-know-about-miss-pakistan-world-2016/</ref> was in the media<ref>https://www.parhlo.com/8-amazing-things-you-didnt-know-about-miss-pakistan-world-2016/</ref> in Pakistan for being criticized for representing [[Pakistan]] and there was discussions on how she is not Pakistani and should represent [[Ukraine]] only. In 2018<ref>https://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-supranational/beauty-queens-from-india-and-pakistan-spread-the-message-of-peace/articleshow/66863581.cms</ref>, a photo of Miss India and Miss Pakistan World, [[Anzhelika Tahir]] went viral as both the beauty queens were holding their respective flags and calling out for peace between Pakistan and India. \n\nOn December 1, 2019<ref>https://nypost.com/2019/12/04/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-killed-in-car-crash/</ref> at 11:40 PM, former Miss Pakistan World 2012, [[Zanib Naveed]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianbazaar.com/migrating-to-Canada/zainab-naveed-miss-pakistan-world-2012/|title=Zainab Naveed Miss Pakistan World 2012|last=admin|date=2012-08-31|website=The Canadian Bazaar|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> died in a car crash accident. According to the police<ref>https://www.brecorder.com/2019/12/04/550282/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-dies-in-car-crash/</ref>, she attempted to take a curve to Route 1 and her vehicle struck a curb and flipped over. She<ref>https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/04-Dec-2019/former-miss-pakistan-dies-in-car-crash-in-usa</ref> was ejected from the vehicle and died at the scene. Alcohol did not appear to be a factor in the crash, according to a preliminary investigation. Naveed<ref>https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/briarcliff/news/32-year-old-area-woman-killed-in-crash-was-miss-pakistan-world/780057/</ref> was the only person<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/new-york-woman-killed-in-crash-along-icc-in-college-park-area/2019/12/02/1103c724-1518-11ea-8406-df3c54b3253e_story.html</ref> in the car.\n\nOn December 5th, 2019, [[Sonia Ahmed]]<ref>http://www.itssouthasian.com/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-dies-in-a-car-crash/</ref> President of Miss Pakistan World was interviewed by [[People (magazine)]]<ref>https://people.com/human-interest/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-dies-car-crash/</ref> Los Angeles USA for the untimely death of one of the winners of Miss Pakistan World [[Zanib Naveed]]. Ahmed answered, \u201cAs the President of Miss Pakistan World, we gave Naveed an amazing platform to represent Pakistan internationally and hearing about her death is very upsetting to all of us,\u201d Ahmed said. \u201cBeing a beauty queen to a country like Pakistan where there have been no beauty pageants on the soil of Pakistan is a tough job!\u201d \u201cNaveed along with other winners of Miss Pakistan World had a huge responsibility of carrying the title of a Muslim Nation,\u201d she continued. \u201cIt is a very upsetting time and terrible news and we can all hope and pray that her family gets through this painful situation.\u201d\n\n==Expansion==\n\nIn 2007 Mrs. Pakistan World,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.finance.yahoo.com/news/pakistan-gets-mrs-pakistan-world-221800650.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412051958/http://ca.finance.yahoo.com/news/pakistan-gets-mrs-pakistan-world-221800650.html |archivedate=2013-04-12 }}</ref> for married women, was created as a spin-off. Both the Miss Pakistan World and the Mrs. Pakistan World pageant were created on the basis of issues faced by [[women in Pakistan]].The pageant is running successfully since 2007.\n\nIn 2011 Mr. Pakistan World, for single males of Pakistani descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barbiedressupgames.site/|title=Meet the new Mr. Pakistan World|website=pageantcenter.com}}</ref> The pageant has been running since 2011 and has been incorporated with the Miss Pakistan World pageant on stage.\n\nIn 2016, [[Sonia Ahmed]] got successful sending the first delegate directly from [[Pakistan]] to represent Pakistan in international pageants. Diya Ali<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1648074/4-lahore-based-diya-ali-participate-miss-eco-international-2018/</ref> was the first representative from Pakistan<ref>https://images.dawn.com/news/1176877</ref> in 2016, and won the Miss Perpetual<ref>http://tribune.com.pk/story/1281667/pakistani-model-aiming-miss-world-title/</ref> title in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]] at the [[Miss Asia Pacific International]] pageant. That created a base for sending contestants directly from Pakistan for Miss Pakistan, Mrs. Pakistan and Mr. Pakistan, all new contests for Pakistan only.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sonia Ahmed]]\n* [http://www.mrspakistan.com Mrs. Pakistan World]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.misspakistanworld.com/ Miss Pakistan World] website\n* ''[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-04-17/pakistan/27750143_1_pakistan-president-pervez-musharraf-hunk-pageants I want to date Mush the hunk]'', India Times article about one of the pageant's winners\n* ''[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Sania-bhabhi-must-stay-in-Pak/articleshow/5762816.cms Miss Pakistan 2009 comments on Sania & Shoaib Marriage]'', [[Times of India]]\n\n{{Miss Earth countries and territories}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistani awards]]\n[[Category:Women in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Miss Pakistan World winners|*]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants in Canada]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageants for people of specific ethnic or national descents]]\n", "name_user": "Salut65", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miss_Pakistan_World"}
{"title_page": "Tajiks of Xinjiang", "text_new": "{{short description|Ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Mountain Tajiks\n|image=[[File:\u65b0\u7586\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf\u7267\u6c11.jpg|250px]]\n|pop=41,028 (Xinjiang of China)<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/EthnicGroups/136950.htm|title=The Tajik Ethnic Group|accessdate=2007-12-10|date=June 21, 2005|publisher=China.org.cn}}</ref> 1,000~2,000 (Sarikoli in [[Tajikistan]])<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Research on Bilingual Phenomenon of Tajiks in Kashgar Prefecture|journal=Language and Translation|issn=1001-0823|author=Pam Arlund|year=2000|issue=1|volume=61|pages=12|id=|url=http://www.xjass.com/ls/content/2008-11/15/content_40826.htm|accessdate=2009-03-27|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718131543/http://www.xjass.com/ls/content/2008-11/15/content_40826.htm|archivedate=2011-07-18|df=}}</ref>\n|popplace=[[Taxkorgan Tajik Autonomous County]]\n|langs=[[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli]] (majority), [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] (minority), [[Mandarin Chinese]]\n|rels=[[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Aga Khani]] [[Nizari]] [[Ismailism]]\n|related=[[Iranian peoples]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Chinese Tajiks''' or '''Mountain Tajiks in China''' ([[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli]]: {{IPA-fo|tud\u0292ik|}}, ''Tujik''; {{zh|c={{linktext|\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf}}|p=T\u01cej\u00edk\u00e8 Z\u00fa}}), including Sarikolis (majority) and [[Wakhi people|Wakhis]] (minority) in China, are an extension of the [[Pamiri people|Pamiri]] ethnic group that lives in the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]] in the [[China|People's Republic of China]]. They are one of the 56 [[List of ethnic groups in China|ethnic groups]] officially recognized by the government of China.\n\n==Name==\n{{See also|Pamiri people}}\n\nDespite the name by which they are known in China, the Tajiks of Xinjiang are not the same as the [[Tajiks|Tajik people]] (who speak the [[Tajik language]]). The Tajiks in Xinjiang of China, are an extension of the [[Pamiri people]], a different Iranian group who speak the indigenous Eastern Iranian [[Pamiri languages]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early period ===\n[[Tashkurgan Town]] became the capital of the [[Sarikol kingdom]] (\u8272\u52d2\u5e93\u5c14), a kingdom of the Pamir Mountains.\n\n=== Medieval period ===\nXinjiang and its eastern Iranian-speaking peoples underwent gradual Turkification caused by the conquests and settlements of Turkic peoples like the [[Uyghurs]] and [[Kara-Khanid Khanate|Qarakhanids]]. By the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol period]], most of these eastern Iranian peoples were assimilated into the Turkic community. The Tajiks of Xinjiang claim to be descended from the remaining eastern Iranians who still resided in the mountainous region of Xinjiang. This claim is seemingly supported by medieval Chinese literature, documents and modern archaeological evidence.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Conversion to Nizari Ismailism ===\nAccording to oral tradition, [[Nasir Khusraw]] led a mission to the region with four of his disciples: Sayyid Hassan Zarrabi, Sayyid Surab Wali, Sayyid Jalal Bukhari, and Jahan Malikshah. Khusraw purportedly told some of his disciples to settle down in the area to continue to aid and preach to the local converts about [[Isma'ilism|Ismailism]]. Many current ''pirs'' (holy men) claim descent from these early disciples.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Qing dynasty ===\nDuring the [[Qing dynasty]], the Tajiks were administered by a system of [[Baig|Begs]] like the rest of [[Xinjiang]]. During the Qing dynasty the Chinese claimed suzerainty over the [[Taghdumbash Pamir]] in the south west of [[Tashkurgan Tajik Autonomous County]] but permitted the [[Mir of Hunza]] to administer the region in return for a [[List of tributaries of Imperial China|tribute]].\n\nThe Tajiks of Xinjiang practiced slavery, selling some of their own as a punishment. Submissive slaves were given wives and settled with the Tajiks. They were considered property and could be sold anytime. Their slaves came from numerous sources, enslaving Sunni captives such as Kirghiz in retaliation for Kirghiz slave raids against the Tajiks since the Kirghiz sold them into slavery in these raids, or from [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] (also known as Khujund), [[Gilgit]], and [[Chitral (princely state)|Chitral]]. Slaves from Chitral and Kunjud passed through there to [[Bukhara]]. The Sunnis called them Rafidites and did not consider them Muslim (as [[Slavery in Islam|enslaving fellow Muslims]] is contrary to [[Sharia|Sharia law]]).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JxwPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA56&dq=tajiks+kirghiz+enslave#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Report of a mission to Yarkund in 1873, under command of Sir T. D. Forsyth: with historical and geographical information regarding the possessions of the ameer of Yarkund|author=[[Sir Thomas Douglas Forsyth]]|year=1875|publisher=Printed at the Foreign department press|location=|page=56|isbn=|accessdate=2011-01-23}}</ref>\n\nMost foreign slaves in Xinjiang were Shia Mountain Tajiks, they were referred to by Sunni Turkic Muslims as Ghalcha.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NKCU3BdeBbEC&pg=PA20&dq=xinjiang+trade+banned+by+qianlong+bek+system+serfs#v=onepage&q=xinjiang%20trade%20banned%20by%20qianlong%20bek%20system%20serfs&f=false|title=Situating the Uyghurs between China and Central Asia|author=Ildik\u00f3 Bell\u00e9r-Hann|year=2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd|isbn=978-0-7546-7041-4|page=20|accessdate=2010-07-30}}</ref> Shia Mountain Tajik Ghalchas made up the majority of slave trafficked and sold in Xinjiang to the Sunni Muslim Turkic inhabitants and they were seen as foreigners and strangers. Serfs were treated in a \"wretched\" manner.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2016 |title=Situating the Uyghurs Between China and Central Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JO24DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT68#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher=Routledge |page=20 |isbn=978-1351899895 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nAn anti-Russian uproar broke out when Russian customs officials, 3 Cossacks and a Russian courier invited local [[Prostitution in China#Xinjiang|Turki Muslim (Uyghur) prostitutes]] to a party in January 1902 in [[Kashgar]], this caused a massive brawl by the inflamed local Turki Muslim populace against the Russians on the pretense of protecting Muslim women because there was anti-Russian sentiment being built up, even though morality was not strict in Kashgar, the local Turki Muslims violently clashed with the Russians before they were dispersed, the Chinese sought an end to tensions to prevent the Russians from building up a pretext to invade.<ref name=\"NightingaleSkrine2013\" /><ref name=\"NightingaleSkrine2013\">{{cite book|author1=Pamela Nightingale|author2=C.P. Skrine|title=Macartney at Kashgar: New Light on British, Chinese and Russian Activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Bbr5AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT126&dq=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar#v=onepage|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-57616-4|pages=124\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"SkrineNightingale1973\">{{cite book|author1=Sir Clarmont Percival Skrine|author2=Pamela Nightingale|title=Macartney at Kashgar: new light on British, Chinese and Russian activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0DgIAQAAIAAJ&q=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar&dq=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar|year=1973|publisher=Methuen|page=124}}</ref>\n\nAfter the riot, the Russians sent troops to Sarikol in Tashkurghan and demanded that the Sarikol postal services be placed under Russian supervision, the locals of Sarikol believed that the Russians would seize the entire district from the Chinese and send more soldiers even after the Russians tried to negotiate with the Begs of Sarikol and sway them to their side, they failed since the Sarikoli officials and authorities demanded in a petition to the Amban of Yarkand that they be evacuated to Yarkand to avoid being harassed by the Russians and objected to the Russian presence in Sarikol, the Sarikolis did not believe the Russian claim that they would leave them alone and only involved themselves in the mail service.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pamela Nightingale|author2=C.P. Skrine|title=Macartney at Kashgar: New Light on British, Chinese and Russian Activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lTn-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA125&dq=100+petty+Sarikol+protested+against+Russians+molest#v=onepage|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-57609-6|pages=125\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Sir Clarmont Percival Skrine|author2=Pamela Nightingale|title=Macartney at Kashgar: new light on British, Chinese and Russian activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0DgIAQAAIAAJ&q=On+8+February+a+deputation+from+Sarikol+arrived+at+Yarkand+and+presented+to+the+Amban+three+petitions+which+bore+the+seals+of+six+headmen+and+the+thumb-marks+of+about+100+petty+Sarikol+officials.+They+protested+against+the+arrival+of+the+Russians+and+asked+to+be+given+land+near+Yarkand+as+they+were+certain+that+the+Russians+would+molest+them.&dq=On+8+February+a+deputation+from+Sarikol+arrived+at+Yarkand+and+presented+to+the+Amban+three+petitions+which+bore+the+seals+of+six+headmen+and+the+thumb-marks+of+about+100+petty+Sarikol+officials.+They+protested+against+the+arrival+of+the+Russians+and+asked+to+be+given+land+near+Yarkand+as+they+were+certain+that+the+Russians+would+molest+them.|year=1973|publisher=Methuen|page=125}}</ref>\n\n===Republic of China===\n\nIn the 1940s around 9,000 Tajiks lived in Xinjiang.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=warlords+and+muslims#v=snippet&q=tajiks%20sarikol%209%2C000&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911\u20131949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=6|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ili Rebellion]], Uyghur forces butchered the livestock of the Tajiks as they advanced south.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aY9ImH3Vna8C&pg=PA488&dq=china+tajik+turki#v=onepage&q=china%20tajik%20turki&f=false|title=Eric Shipton: The Six Mountain-Travel Books|author=Eric Shipton, Jim Perrin|year=1997|publisher=The Mountaineers Books|location=|isbn=0-89886-539-5|page=488|accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> The Soviet backed insurgents destroyed Tajik crops and acted aggressively against the Tajiks and Kirghiz of China.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=warlords+and+muslims#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20antagonised&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911\u20131949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=204|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe population of Tajiks in China numbered 41,028 in 2000 and 50,265 (Xinjiang only)<ref name=\"2015xjpopulation\"/> in 2015. They are located in [[China]]'s western [[Xinjiang]] region with 60% living in [[Tashkurgan Tajik Autonomous County]]. Despite the name \"Tajik\" that is used to refer to them, the Tajiks of China do not speak the [[Tajik language]]. Early 20th-century travelers to the region referred to them as Sarikoli,<ref>A Journey of Geographical and Archarological Exploration in Chinese Turkestan\nA Stein \u2013 1904 \u2013 [sn]\n... 15,800 feet above the sea, into Chinese territory on the Taghdumbash Pamir, using\nthe yaks of the Sarikoli herdsmen...</ref><ref>The Heart of a Continent \u2013 Younghusband \u2013 ...an encampment belonging to a Sarikoli, who very kindly asked me to have some refreshment... (pg 242)</ref> \"Mountain Tajiks,\"<ref>Through the Unknown Pamirs; the Second Danish Pamir Expedition 1898\u201399 By Ole Olufsen</ref> or Ghalcha.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9skBUtc0YTwC&pg=PA71&dq=tajiks+ghalchas+mountain+tajiks+iranian+speaking#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20ghalchas%20mountain%20tajiks%20iranian%20speaking&f=false|title=The Cambridge history of China, Volume 10|author=Denis Crispin Twitchett, John King Fairbank|year=1977|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=|page=71|isbn=0-521-21447-5|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref> As of 2015-16, more than four thousand Mountain Tajiks lived in nearby [[Poskam County]] (Zepu).<ref name=\"poskamgaikuang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xjzp.gov.cn/P/C/8348.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126215741/http://www.xjzp.gov.cn/P/C/8348.htm|archivedate=26 January 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]|script-title=zh:\u6cfd\u666e\u6982\u51b5|language=zh-hans|website={{lang|zh-hans|\u6cfd\u666e\u653f\u5e9c\u7f51}}|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=10 April 2020|quote={{lang|zh-hans|2016\u5e74\u672b\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u603b\u6237\u6570\uff08\u542b\u5854\u897f\u5357\u52d8\u63a2\u5f00\u53d1\u516c\u53f8\uff0965684\u6237\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\u53bf\u5c5e\u6237\u657059804\u6237\uff1b\u603b\u4eba\u53e3208950\u4eba\uff08\u542b\u5854\u897f\u5357\u52d8\u63a2\u5f00\u53d1\u516c\u53f8\uff09\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf175686\u4eba\uff0c\u536084.1\uff05\uff0c\u6c49\u65cf27131\u4eba\uff0c\u536013\uff05\uff0c\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf4463\u4eba\uff0c\u53602.1\uff05\uff0c\u5176\u4ed6\u6c11\u65cf1670\u4eba\uff0c\u53600.8\uff05\u3002}}}}</ref><ref name=\"2015xjpopulation\">{{cite web |url= http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |script-title= zh:3-7 \u5404\u5730\u3001\u5dde\u3001\u5e02\u3001\u53bf(\u5e02)\u5206\u6c11\u65cf\u4eba\u53e3\u6570 |language=zh-hans|publisher={{lang|ug|\u0634\u0649\u0646\u062c\u0627\u06ad \u0626\u06c7\u064a\u063a\u06c7\u0631 \u0626\u0627\u067e\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0648\u0645 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}} {{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40}} Statistic Bureau of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region |date=15 March 2017|access-date=3 September 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011101904/http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |archive-date= 11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Language==\nIn China, the languages of the Tajik people have no official written form.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wEih57-GWQQC&pg=PA71&dq=tajiks+darian+china#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20darian%20china&f=false|title=Guide to Islamist Movements|author=BARRY RUBIN|year=2000|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|location=|page=71|isbn=0-7656-1747-1|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref> The great majority speak the [[Sarikoli language]], which has been heavily influenced by [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], an [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]].<ref name=arlund1>{{cite book |title= An Acoustic, Historical, And Developmental Analysis Of Sarikol Tajik Diphthongs. Ph.D Dissertation |last=Arlund |first= Pamela S. |authorlink= |year=2006 |publisher= The University of Texas at Arlington |location= |isbn= |page=191 |url= http://repositories.tdl.org/tdl/handle/10106/438 |accessdate=}}</ref> A small proportion speaks the [[Wakhi language]].<ref name=felmy>{{cite book |title=The voice of the nightingale: a personal account of the Wakhi culture in Hunza |last=Felmy |first=Sabine |authorlink= |year=1996 |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |location= [[Karachi]] |isbn= 0-19-577599-6 |page=4 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=gTtuAAAAMAAJ&q}}</ref> Sarikoli and Wakhi are [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] languages, commonly classified in the [[Pamir languages|Pamir]] or [[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern Iranian]] areal groups.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IOM8qF34s4YC&pg=PA319&dq=tajiks+china#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20china&f=false|title=An ethnohistorical dictionary of China|author=James Stuart Olson|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=|page=319|isbn=0-313-28853-4|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n{{Islam and China|groups}}\nThe Mountain Tajiks in China are adherents of the [[Aga Khani]] [[Nizari]] [[Ismailism|Ismaili sect]] of [[Shia Islam]], and are still a little isolated from the rest of the worldwide Ismaili community, though their communication with other Pamiri (Ismaili) peoples has never stopped. The Chinese authorities allow a few Ismaili religious buildings to function in Xinjiang's Tajik Autonomous District, whose clerics were appointed by the Chinese secular authorities. Restrictions by the Chinese government bars foreign Ismaili preachers from openly working among the Tajiks in China; and the religious leader of the Nizari Ismaili sect, the [[Aga Khan]], was once barred from business with the [[China]]'s Ismailis.<ref>UNHCR Refworld, [http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/46891841d.html CHINA: Xinjiang's Ismailis cut off from international Ismaili community] [accessed 13 May 2009]</ref> \n\nFrom 2\u20134 April 2012, His Highness the [[Aga Khan]] ([[Aga Khan IV]]), paid an official visit to \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, China, at the invitation of the Governor of the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region, Mr [[Nur Bekri]], to discuss collaboration between the [[Aga Khan Development Network]] (AKDN) and the autonomous government of [[Xinjiang]]. His Highness and Governor Bekri held constructive talks in the meeting and agreed to collaborate in several thematic areas of mutual interest, including poverty alleviation, education, tourism investment, and financial services.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.akdn.org/Content/1125 |title = The Aga Khan visits Western China &#124; Aga Khan Development Network}}</ref> The [[Aga Khan IV]] had last visited China in 1981.\n\nChina's Tajiks have been caught up in the country's crackdown on Muslims that has taken place since 2017, despite the fact that they have not tended to be politically active and the repressions have mainly targeted Uighurs. Only a single mosque is allowed to operate in the Tajik region, and children under 18 are not permitted to attend it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East|last=Foltz|first=Richard|publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]]|year=2019|isbn=978-1-83860-446-2|location=New York|pages=185|author-link=Richard Foltz}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Family Life ===\nIn an average traditional family, at least three or more generations of relatives live under the same household. There's also a hierarchy which is determined by a family member's age and gender but the senior male stands as the head of the family. The responsibilities of the men tend to be providing for the family and looking after the children and elderly. The women's responsibilities are to raise the children, do household duties, and to attend to the elderly. The senior male is in charge of managing the entire household and the family's wealth through consulting with the rest of the men in the house. The young men are discouraged from seeking an independent life outside the household unless they get consent from the family. Failure to do so can forfeit them from inheritance. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1mGJDwAAQBAJ&vq=Ismailis+of+China|title=A Modern History of the Ismailis: Continuity and Change in a Muslim Community|last=Saidula|first=Amier|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2011|isbn=9781845117177|editor-last=Daftary|editor-first=Farhad|location=London and New York|pages=77\u201391|chapter=The Nizari Ismailis of China in Modern Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Rites of passage and life cycles ===\nMarriages are usually arranged by the parents of the prospective groom and bride from the asking of the daughter's hand up to the wedding. The families of the couple also decide on the dowry amount, plan the engagements and wedding dates, and choose who can attend. Some three days before the wedding, the families come together and initiate a feast for the people in the area who have lost relatives in the last year or so. These people then approve of the celebration by tapping on a hand drum.<ref name=\":0\" /> Funerals are conducted by first doing the Islamic rites of cleansing the body and praying for the deceased. This is followed by the family who burn incense and close any room or ceiling windows as this is believed to purify the path for the deceased. Every family member is expected to attend the funeral or make up for it with a visit to the family. For forty days after the burial, the closest relatives of the deceased will begin to abstain from personal comforts like by keeping their hair unkempt or uncut. On the last day, friends and family come together to bathe and clean the mourners and to convince them to return to their daily lives.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Festivals and rituals ===\nThe two main celebrations of the Tajiks of Xinjiang are the [[Nowruz]] (Persian New Year) and the ''Pilik'' festival. Right before Nowruz or \"''ched chader''\" in Sariqoli (meaning cleaning the house') begins, families rigorously clean their homes and sprinkle the inner walls with ''putuk'' (wheat flour) to wish for a successful year. Each household bakes a cake for the occasion to share with guests. The guests are welcomed on the doorstep by dusting some ''putuk'' on their right shoulder. ''Pilik'' is dedicated to commemorate the dead. Families light candles and pray for the souls of the dead while circling the light and pulling the flame towards their face. This ritual lasts two days. On the first day, families ight candles inside the house. On the second day, they visit the local cemetery and light a candle for each deceased relative and place it on their graves.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSeasonal rituals like the ''Zuwur zoht'' (irrigation) and ''Teghm zuwost'' (seed sowing) used to be commonplace but presently a ''pir'' (a local religious master) ''or khalifa'' (a religious functionary who trained under a pir) blesses the agricultural implements in the fields by reciting verses from the Quran.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Livelihood ===\nBecause of the harsh and scarce environment in which the locals live in, they mostly rely on cultivating whatever arable land is available and engage in small-scale animal husbandry. Other types of subsistence also include selling traditional embroidery, clothes, hats, and other arts and crafts. However, this is only a seasonal operation. There are also a few governmental wages available but salaried jobs are few and the demand is very high.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.china.org.cn/e-groups/shaoshu/shao-2-tajik.htm The Tajik ethnic minority (China)] (government website, in English)\n\n{{-}}\n{{Xinjiang topics}}\n{{Iranian peoples}}\n{{CEG}}\n\n\n[[Category:Tajiks of Xinjiang| ]]\n[[Category:Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Tajik people|Xingjiang]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of China]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups officially recognized by China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Mountain Tajiks\n|image=[[File:\u65b0\u7586\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf\u7267\u6c11.jpg|250px]]\n|pop=41,028 (Xinjiang of China)<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/EthnicGroups/136950.htm|title=The Tajik Ethnic Group|accessdate=2007-12-10|date=June 21, 2005|publisher=China.org.cn}}</ref> 1,000~2,000 (Sarikoli in [[Tajikistan]])<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Research on Bilingual Phenomenon of Tajiks in Kashgar Prefecture|journal=Language and Translation|issn=1001-0823|author=Pam Arlund|year=2000|issue=1|volume=61|pages=12|id=|url=http://www.xjass.com/ls/content/2008-11/15/content_40826.htm|accessdate=2009-03-27|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718131543/http://www.xjass.com/ls/content/2008-11/15/content_40826.htm|archivedate=2011-07-18|df=}}</ref>\n|popplace=[[Taxkorgan Tajik Autonomous County]]\n|langs=[[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli]] (majority), [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] (minority), [[Mandarin Chinese]]\n|rels=[[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Aga Khani]] [[Nizari]] [[Ismailism]]\n|related=[[Iranian peoples]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Chinese Tajiks''' or '''Mountain Tajiks in China''' ([[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli]]: {{IPA-fo|tud\u0292ik|}}, ''Tujik''; {{zh|c={{linktext|\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf}}|p=T\u01cej\u00edk\u00e8 Z\u00fa}}), including Sarikolis (majority) and [[Wakhi people|Wakhis]] (minority) in China, are an extension of the [[Pamiri people|Pamiri]] ethnic group that lives in the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]] in the [[China|People's Republic of China]]. They are one of the 56 [[List of ethnic groups in China|ethnic groups]] officially recognized by the government of China.\n\n==Name==\n{{See also|Pamiri people}}\n\nDespite the name by which they are known in China, the Tajiks of Xinjiang are not the same as the [[Tajiks|Tajik people]] (who speak the [[Tajik language]]). The Tajiks in Xinjiang of China, are an extension of the [[Pamiri people]], a different Iranian group who speak the indigenous Eastern Iranian [[Pamiri languages]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early period ===\n[[Tashkurgan Town]] became the capital of the [[Sarikol kingdom]] (\u8272\u52d2\u5e93\u5c14), a kingdom of the Pamir Mountains.\n\n=== Medieval period ===\nXinjiang and its eastern Iranian-speaking peoples underwent gradual Turkification caused by the conquests and settlements of Turkic peoples like the [[Uyghurs]] and [[Kara-Khanid Khanate|Qarakhanids]]. By the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol period]], most of these eastern Iranian peoples were assimilated into the Turkic community. The Tajiks of Xinjiang claim to be descended from the remaining eastern Iranians who still resided in the mountainous region of Xinjiang. This claim is seemingly supported by medieval Chinese literature, documents and modern archaeological evidence.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Conversion to Nizari Ismailism ===\nAccording to oral tradition, [[Nasir Khusraw]] led a mission to the region with four of his disciples: Sayyid Hassan Zarrabi, Sayyid Surab Wali, Sayyid Jalal Bukhari, and Jahan Malikshah. Khusraw purportedly told some of his disciples to settle down in the area to continue to aid and preach to the local converts about [[Isma'ilism|Ismailism]]. Many current ''pirs'' (holy men) claim descent from these early disciples.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Qing dynasty ===\nDuring the [[Qing dynasty]], the Tajiks were administered by a system of [[Baig|Begs]] like the rest of [[Xinjiang]]. During the Qing dynasty the Chinese claimed suzerainty over the [[Taghdumbash Pamir]] in the south west of [[Tashkurgan Tajik Autonomous County]] but permitted the [[Mir of Hunza]] to administer the region in return for a [[List of tributaries of Imperial China|tribute]].\n\nThe Tajiks of Xinjiang practiced slavery, selling some of their own as a punishment. Submissive slaves were given wives and settled with the Tajiks. They were considered property and could be sold anytime. Their slaves came from numerous sources, enslaving Sunni captives such as Kirghiz in retaliation for Kirghiz slave raids against the Tajiks since the Kirghiz sold them into slavery in these raids, or from [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] (also known as Khujund), [[Gilgit]], and [[Chitral (princely state)|Chitral]]. Slaves from Chitral and Kunjud passed through there to [[Bukhara]]. The Sunnis called them Rafidites and did not consider them Muslim (as e[[Slavery in Islam|nslaving fellow Muslims]] is contrary to [[Sharia|Sharia law]]).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JxwPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA56&dq=tajiks+kirghiz+enslave#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Report of a mission to Yarkund in 1873, under command of Sir T. D. Forsyth: with historical and geographical information regarding the possessions of the ameer of Yarkund|author=[[Sir Thomas Douglas Forsyth]]|year=1875|publisher=Printed at the Foreign department press|location=|page=56|isbn=|accessdate=2011-01-23}}</ref>\n\nMost foreign slaves in Xinjiang were Shia Mountain Tajiks, they were referred to by Sunni Turkic Muslims as Ghalcha.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NKCU3BdeBbEC&pg=PA20&dq=xinjiang+trade+banned+by+qianlong+bek+system+serfs#v=onepage&q=xinjiang%20trade%20banned%20by%20qianlong%20bek%20system%20serfs&f=false|title=Situating the Uyghurs between China and Central Asia|author=Ildik\u00f3 Bell\u00e9r-Hann|year=2007|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd|isbn=978-0-7546-7041-4|page=20|accessdate=2010-07-30}}</ref> Shia Mountain Tajik Ghalchas made up the majority of slave trafficked and sold in Xinjiang to the Sunni Muslim Turkic inhabitants and they were seen as foreigners and strangers. Serfs were treated in a \"wretched\" manner.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2016 |title=Situating the Uyghurs Between China and Central Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JO24DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT68#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher=Routledge |page=20 |isbn=978-1351899895 |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nAn anti-Russian uproar broke out when Russian customs officials, 3 Cossacks and a Russian courier invited local [[Prostitution in China#Xinjiang|Turki Muslim (Uyghur) prostitutes]] to a party in January 1902 in [[Kashgar]], this caused a massive brawl by the inflamed local Turki Muslim populace against the Russians on the pretense of protecting Muslim women because there was anti-Russian sentiment being built up, even though morality was not strict in Kashgar, the local Turki Muslims violently clashed with the Russians before they were dispersed, the Chinese sought an end to tensions to prevent the Russians from building up a pretext to invade.<ref name=\"NightingaleSkrine2013\" /><ref name=\"NightingaleSkrine2013\">{{cite book|author1=Pamela Nightingale|author2=C.P. Skrine|title=Macartney at Kashgar: New Light on British, Chinese and Russian Activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Bbr5AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT126&dq=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar#v=onepage|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-57616-4|pages=124\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"SkrineNightingale1973\">{{cite book|author1=Sir Clarmont Percival Skrine|author2=Pamela Nightingale|title=Macartney at Kashgar: new light on British, Chinese and Russian activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0DgIAQAAIAAJ&q=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar&dq=Russian+couriers+three+Cossacks+Russian+customs+native+prostitutes+Kashgar|year=1973|publisher=Methuen|page=124}}</ref>\n\nAfter the riot, the Russians sent troops to Sarikol in Tashkurghan and demanded that the Sarikol postal services be placed under Russian supervision, the locals of Sarikol believed that the Russians would seize the entire district from the Chinese and send more soldiers even after the Russians tried to negotiate with the Begs of Sarikol and sway them to their side, they failed since the Sarikoli officials and authorities demanded in a petition to the Amban of Yarkand that they be evacuated to Yarkand to avoid being harassed by the Russians and objected to the Russian presence in Sarikol, the Sarikolis did not believe the Russian claim that they would leave them alone and only involved themselves in the mail service.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pamela Nightingale|author2=C.P. Skrine|title=Macartney at Kashgar: New Light on British, Chinese and Russian Activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lTn-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA125&dq=100+petty+Sarikol+protested+against+Russians+molest#v=onepage|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-57609-6|pages=125\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Sir Clarmont Percival Skrine|author2=Pamela Nightingale|title=Macartney at Kashgar: new light on British, Chinese and Russian activities in Sinkiang, 1890-1918|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0DgIAQAAIAAJ&q=On+8+February+a+deputation+from+Sarikol+arrived+at+Yarkand+and+presented+to+the+Amban+three+petitions+which+bore+the+seals+of+six+headmen+and+the+thumb-marks+of+about+100+petty+Sarikol+officials.+They+protested+against+the+arrival+of+the+Russians+and+asked+to+be+given+land+near+Yarkand+as+they+were+certain+that+the+Russians+would+molest+them.&dq=On+8+February+a+deputation+from+Sarikol+arrived+at+Yarkand+and+presented+to+the+Amban+three+petitions+which+bore+the+seals+of+six+headmen+and+the+thumb-marks+of+about+100+petty+Sarikol+officials.+They+protested+against+the+arrival+of+the+Russians+and+asked+to+be+given+land+near+Yarkand+as+they+were+certain+that+the+Russians+would+molest+them.|year=1973|publisher=Methuen|page=125}}</ref>\n\n===Republic of China===\n\nIn the 1940s around 9,000 Tajiks lived in Xinjiang.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=warlords+and+muslims#v=snippet&q=tajiks%20sarikol%209%2C000&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911\u20131949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=6|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ili Rebellion]], Uyghur forces butchered the livestock of the Tajiks as they advanced south.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aY9ImH3Vna8C&pg=PA488&dq=china+tajik+turki#v=onepage&q=china%20tajik%20turki&f=false|title=Eric Shipton: The Six Mountain-Travel Books|author=Eric Shipton, Jim Perrin|year=1997|publisher=The Mountaineers Books|location=|isbn=0-89886-539-5|page=488|accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> The Soviet backed insurgents destroyed Tajik crops and acted aggressively against the Tajiks and Kirghiz of China.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IAs9AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=warlords+and+muslims#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20antagonised&f=false|title=Warlords and Muslims in Chinese Central Asia: a political history of Republican Sinkiang 1911\u20131949|author=Andrew D. W. Forbes|year=1986|publisher=CUP Archive|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=0-521-25514-7|page=204|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe population of Tajiks in China numbered 41,028 in 2000 and 50,265 (Xinjiang only)<ref name=\"2015xjpopulation\"/> in 2015. They are located in [[China]]'s western [[Xinjiang]] region with 60% living in [[Tashkurgan Tajik Autonomous County]]. Despite the name \"Tajik\" that is used to refer to them, the Tajiks of China do not speak the [[Tajik language]]. Early 20th-century travelers to the region referred to them as Sarikoli,<ref>A Journey of Geographical and Archarological Exploration in Chinese Turkestan\nA Stein \u2013 1904 \u2013 [sn]\n... 15,800 feet above the sea, into Chinese territory on the Taghdumbash Pamir, using\nthe yaks of the Sarikoli herdsmen...</ref><ref>The Heart of a Continent \u2013 Younghusband \u2013 ...an encampment belonging to a Sarikoli, who very kindly asked me to have some refreshment... (pg 242)</ref> \"Mountain Tajiks,\"<ref>Through the Unknown Pamirs; the Second Danish Pamir Expedition 1898\u201399 By Ole Olufsen</ref> or Ghalcha.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9skBUtc0YTwC&pg=PA71&dq=tajiks+ghalchas+mountain+tajiks+iranian+speaking#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20ghalchas%20mountain%20tajiks%20iranian%20speaking&f=false|title=The Cambridge history of China, Volume 10|author=Denis Crispin Twitchett, John King Fairbank|year=1977|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=|page=71|isbn=0-521-21447-5|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref> As of 2015-16, more than four thousand Mountain Tajiks lived in nearby [[Poskam County]] (Zepu).<ref name=\"poskamgaikuang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xjzp.gov.cn/P/C/8348.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126215741/http://www.xjzp.gov.cn/P/C/8348.htm|archivedate=26 January 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]|script-title=zh:\u6cfd\u666e\u6982\u51b5|language=zh-hans|website={{lang|zh-hans|\u6cfd\u666e\u653f\u5e9c\u7f51}}|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=10 April 2020|quote={{lang|zh-hans|2016\u5e74\u672b\uff0c\u5168\u53bf\u603b\u6237\u6570\uff08\u542b\u5854\u897f\u5357\u52d8\u63a2\u5f00\u53d1\u516c\u53f8\uff0965684\u6237\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\u53bf\u5c5e\u6237\u657059804\u6237\uff1b\u603b\u4eba\u53e3208950\u4eba\uff08\u542b\u5854\u897f\u5357\u52d8\u63a2\u5f00\u53d1\u516c\u53f8\uff09\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d\uff0c\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u65cf175686\u4eba\uff0c\u536084.1\uff05\uff0c\u6c49\u65cf27131\u4eba\uff0c\u536013\uff05\uff0c\u5854\u5409\u514b\u65cf4463\u4eba\uff0c\u53602.1\uff05\uff0c\u5176\u4ed6\u6c11\u65cf1670\u4eba\uff0c\u53600.8\uff05\u3002}}}}</ref><ref name=\"2015xjpopulation\">{{cite web |url= http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |script-title= zh:3-7 \u5404\u5730\u3001\u5dde\u3001\u5e02\u3001\u53bf(\u5e02)\u5206\u6c11\u65cf\u4eba\u53e3\u6570 |language=zh-hans|publisher={{lang|ug|\u0634\u0649\u0646\u062c\u0627\u06ad \u0626\u06c7\u064a\u063a\u06c7\u0631 \u0626\u0627\u067e\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0648\u0645 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}} {{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40}} Statistic Bureau of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region |date=15 March 2017|access-date=3 September 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011101904/http://www.xjtj.gov.cn/sjcx/tjnj_3415/2016xjtjnj/rkjy/201707/t20170714_539450.html |archive-date= 11 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Language==\nIn China, the languages of the Tajik people have no official written form.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wEih57-GWQQC&pg=PA71&dq=tajiks+darian+china#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20darian%20china&f=false|title=Guide to Islamist Movements|author=BARRY RUBIN|year=2000|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|location=|page=71|isbn=0-7656-1747-1|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref> The great majority speak the [[Sarikoli language]], which has been heavily influenced by [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], an [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]].<ref name=arlund1>{{cite book |title= An Acoustic, Historical, And Developmental Analysis Of Sarikol Tajik Diphthongs. Ph.D Dissertation |last=Arlund |first= Pamela S. |authorlink= |year=2006 |publisher= The University of Texas at Arlington |location= |isbn= |page=191 |url= http://repositories.tdl.org/tdl/handle/10106/438 |accessdate=}}</ref> A small proportion speaks the [[Wakhi language]].<ref name=felmy>{{cite book |title=The voice of the nightingale: a personal account of the Wakhi culture in Hunza |last=Felmy |first=Sabine |authorlink= |year=1996 |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |location= [[Karachi]] |isbn= 0-19-577599-6 |page=4 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=gTtuAAAAMAAJ&q}}</ref> Sarikoli and Wakhi are [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] languages, commonly classified in the [[Pamir languages|Pamir]] or [[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern Iranian]] areal groups.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IOM8qF34s4YC&pg=PA319&dq=tajiks+china#v=onepage&q=tajiks%20china&f=false|title=An ethnohistorical dictionary of China|author=James Stuart Olson|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=|page=319|isbn=0-313-28853-4|accessdate=2011-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n{{Islam and China|groups}}\nThe Mountain Tajiks in China are adherents of the [[Aga Khani]] [[Nizari]] [[Ismailism|Ismaili sect]] of [[Shia Islam]], and are still a little isolated from the rest of the worldwide Ismaili community, though their communication with other Pamiri (Ismaili) peoples has never stopped. The Chinese authorities allow a few Ismaili religious buildings to function in Xinjiang's Tajik Autonomous District, whose clerics were appointed by the Chinese secular authorities. Restrictions by the Chinese government bars foreign Ismaili preachers from openly working among the Tajiks in China; and the religious leader of the Nizari Ismaili sect, the [[Aga Khan]], was once barred from business with the [[China]]'s Ismailis.<ref>UNHCR Refworld, [http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/46891841d.html CHINA: Xinjiang's Ismailis cut off from international Ismaili community] [accessed 13 May 2009]</ref> \n\nFrom 2\u20134 April 2012, His Highness the [[Aga Khan]] ([[Aga Khan IV]]), paid an official visit to \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, China, at the invitation of the Governor of the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region, Mr [[Nur Bekri]], to discuss collaboration between the [[Aga Khan Development Network]] (AKDN) and the autonomous government of [[Xinjiang]]. His Highness and Governor Bekri held constructive talks in the meeting and agreed to collaborate in several thematic areas of mutual interest, including poverty alleviation, education, tourism investment, and financial services.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.akdn.org/Content/1125 |title = The Aga Khan visits Western China &#124; Aga Khan Development Network}}</ref> The [[Aga Khan IV]] had last visited China in 1981.\n\nChina's Tajiks have been caught up in the country's crackdown on Muslims that has taken place since 2017, despite the fact that they have not tended to be politically active and the repressions have mainly targeted Uighurs. Only a single mosque is allowed to operate in the Tajik region, and children under 18 are not permitted to attend it.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East|last=Foltz|first=Richard|publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]]|year=2019|isbn=978-1-83860-446-2|location=New York|pages=185|author-link=Richard Foltz}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Family Life ===\nIn an average traditional family, at least three or more generations of relatives live under the same household. There's also a hierarchy which is determined by a family member's age and gender but the senior male stands as the head of the family. The responsibilities of the men tend to be providing for the family and looking after the children and elderly. The women's responsibilities are to raise the children, do household duties, and to attend to the elderly. The senior male is in charge of managing the entire household and the family's wealth through consulting with the rest of the men in the house. The young men are discouraged from seeking an independent life outside the household unless they get consent from the family. Failure to do so can forfeit them from inheritance. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1mGJDwAAQBAJ&vq=Ismailis+of+China|title=A Modern History of the Ismailis: Continuity and Change in a Muslim Community|last=Saidula|first=Amier|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2011|isbn=9781845117177|editor-last=Daftary|editor-first=Farhad|location=London and New York|pages=77\u201391|chapter=The Nizari Ismailis of China in Modern Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Rites of passage and life cycles ===\nMarriages are usually arranged by the parents of the prospective groom and bride from the asking of the daughter's hand up to the wedding. The families of the couple also decide on the dowry amount, plan the engagements and wedding dates, and choose who can attend. Some three days before the wedding, the families come together and initiate a feast for the people in the area who have lost relatives in the last year or so. These people then approve of the celebration by tapping on a hand drum.<ref name=\":0\" /> Funerals are conducted by first doing the Islamic rites of cleansing the body and praying for the deceased. This is followed by the family who burn incense and close any room or ceiling windows as this is believed to purify the path for the deceased. Every family member is expected to attend the funeral or make up for it with a visit to the family. For forty days after the burial, the closest relatives of the deceased will begin to abstain from personal comforts like by keeping their hair unkempt or uncut. On the last day, friends and family come together to bathe and clean the mourners and to convince them to return to their daily lives.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Festivals and rituals ===\nThe two main celebrations of the Tajiks of Xinjiang are the [[Nowruz]] (Persian New Year) and the ''Pilik'' festival. Right before Nowruz or \"''ched chader''\" in Sariqoli (meaning cleaning the house') begins, families rigorously clean their homes and sprinkle the inner walls with ''putuk'' (wheat flour) to wish for a successful year. Each household bakes a cake for the occasion to share with guests. The guests are welcomed on the doorstep by dusting some ''putuk'' on their right shoulder. ''Pilik'' is dedicated to commemorate the dead. Families light candles and pray for the souls of the dead while circling the light and pulling the flame towards their face. This ritual lasts two days. On the first day, families ight candles inside the house. On the second day, they visit the local cemetery and light a candle for each deceased relative and place it on their graves.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSeasonal rituals like the ''Zuwur zoht'' (irrigation) and ''Teghm zuwost'' (seed sowing) used to be commonplace but presently a ''pir'' (a local religious master) ''or khalifa'' (a religious functionary who trained under a pir) blesses the agricultural implements in the fields by reciting verses from the Quran.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Livelihood ===\nBecause of the harsh and scarce environment in which the locals live in, they mostly rely on cultivating whatever arable land is available and engage in small-scale animal husbandry. Other types of subsistence also include selling traditional embroidery, clothes, hats, and other arts and crafts. However, this is only a seasonal operation. There are also a few governmental wages available but salaried jobs are few and the demand is very high.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.china.org.cn/e-groups/shaoshu/shao-2-tajik.htm The Tajik ethnic minority (China)] (government website, in English)\n\n{{-}}\n{{Xinjiang topics}}\n{{Iranian peoples}}\n{{CEG}}\n\n\n[[Category:Tajiks of Xinjiang| ]]\n[[Category:Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Tajik people|Xingjiang]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of China]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups officially recognized by China]]\n", "name_user": "Geographyinitiative", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eQing dynasty", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tajiks_of_Xinjiang"}
{"title_page": "By the Sea (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = By the Sea\n| image = By The Sea Teaser.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Angelina Jolie|Angelina Jolie Pitt]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Angelina Jolie Pitt \n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n}}\n| writer = Angelina Jolie Pitt\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Brad Pitt\n* Angelina Jolie Pitt\n}}\n| music = [[Gabriel Yared]]\n| cinematography = [[Christian Berger]]\n| editing = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Martin Pensa]]\n* Patricia Rommel\n}}\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n*Jolie Pass\n*[[Plan B Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|05|[[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]]|2015|11|13|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:13--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sea-film-1 | title=''BY THE SEA'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 24, 2015 | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* French}}\n| budget = $10 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n| gross = $3.3 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''By the Sea''''' is a 2015 American [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Angelina Jolie Pitt]], and produced by and starring Jolie Pitt and [[Brad Pitt]]. Shot in August 2014 during Pitt and Jolie's [[honeymoon]] in [[Gozo]], [[Malta]], the film was released by [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] on November 13, 2015.\n\nThe film received mixed to negative reviews and was a [[box office bomb]], grossing just $3.3 million against its $10 million budget.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the 1960s, in France, an American couple, former dancer Vanessa and her husband Roland, a successful writer, have been married 14 years. They drive to a coastal hotel. Roland wants to write a story while staying there. The two are barely on speaking terms; Vanessa is withdrawn and grieving for an unknown reason. Roland appears to drink too much and seems unhappy that Vanessa is no longer interested in him sexually.\n\nRoland becomes friendly with the local cafe owner, an older man still grieving his much-loved late wife, but who carries on, cheerfully accepting what life has given him. Vanessa watches a local fisherman who goes out every day on the outgoing tide and returns on the incoming one, catching few fish, but contented.\n\nVanessa and Roland strike up a friendship with an attractive young couple staying in the room next to them. Soon after, they discover that the wall between their two rooms has a disused radiator pipe hole, enabling them to watch the couple in their bedroom talking and having sex.\n\nGradually their experiences at the hotel enable Vanessa and Roland to start patching up their relationship. However, Vanessa attempts a liaison with the young husband in the next room, interrupted violently by Roland, who has been watching through the wall. He bruises the husband, who must later explain to his wife and does so truthfully, seriously damaging the relationship between the young couple. This also triggers a confrontation between Vanessa and Roland, during which he tells her that if she wishes to hurt him, she should just go ahead and hurt him physically. Roland asserts that her seduction of the husband was motivated by his wife's envy of the young couple - particularly of their ability to bear children. Roland physically restrains Vanessa against a wall and makes her speak of herself being barren which they haven't been able to talk about. After a short struggle, Vanessa breaks down and weeps for her loss. Later, Roland explains to the young wife that two miscarriages caused Vanessa's lasting grief, withdrawal and behavior toward her husband.\n\nHaving finally come to terms with their life together, Vanessa seems able to go on and Roland is able to finish writing a new book. It seems also that the young couple next door may be able to work their way through the episode as well, and come out stronger on the other side.\n\nAs Vanessa and Roland leave the hotel and drive away, they appear to be reconciled.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Brad Pitt]] as Roland\n* [[Angelina Jolie|Angelina Jolie Pitt]] as Vanessa\n* [[M\u00e9lanie Laurent]] as L\u00e9a\n* [[Niels Arestrup]] as Michel\n* [[Melvil Poupaud]] as Fran\u00e7ois\n* [[Richard Bohringer]] as Patrice\n\n==Production==\nIn May 2014, it was announced that Angelina Jolie Pitt would co-star with Brad Pitt in a film titled ''By the Sea'', to be written and directed by Jolie.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Universal Buys Angelina Jolie-Brad Pitt Pic Deadline Broke In May|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/universal-buys-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-pic-deadline-broke-in-may/|accessdate=July 19, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=July 18, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' speculated it would be a relationship drama that Jolie Pitt wrote several years ago, centering on a couple with issues who take a vacation in a last-ditch effort to save their marriage.\n\nThis was the first cinematic collaboration between the two since ''[[Mr. & Mrs. Smith (2005 film)|Mr. & Mrs. Smith]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brad-pitt-angelina-jolie-teaming-700953|title=Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie Teaming Up for Mystery Movie Project|date=May 2, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Joseph Muscat]] of [[Malta]] confirmed the project, stating that it would be partially filmed at [[M\u0121arr ix-Xini]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kauri|title=Brangelina are headed to Malta|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/07/14/brangelina-are-headed-to-malta/|accessdate=July 19, 2014|publisher=onlocationvacations.com|date=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20140703/local/angelina-jolie-and-brad-pitt-blockbuster-to-be-filmed-at-mgarr-ix-xini.526135|title=Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt blockbuster to be filmed at Mgarr ix-Xini - timesofmalta.com|work=Times of Malta|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJolie Pitt has stated that the film \"at its core, is about grief\" further noting that the loss of her mother in 2007 caused a great deal of sadness for her.<ref name=mom>{{cite web|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|title='By the Sea' Premiere: Angelina Jolie Pitt on Making a Movie For Her Mother|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/by-sea-premiere-angelina-jolie-837696|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> To that end, the movie resembles movies of the 1960s and '70s; Jolie Pitt stated that her mother \"loved films of that period\".<ref name=mom/>  [[Christian Berger]] is the cinematographer; he used mostly natural light throughout filming,<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood |first=Adam |url=https://collider.com/by-the-sea-images-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt/ |title=By the Sea Images Reveal Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt as a Married Couple |publisher=Collider |date=2014-09-15 |accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref> while [[Jon Hutman]] is the production designer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Caranicas|first1=Peter|title=Below the Line Bookings|url=https://variety.com/2014/artisans/news/below-the-line-bookings-7-1201319626/|accessdate=October 3, 2014|publisher=variety.com|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] and production began on August 19, 2014, in [[Gozo]], [[Malta]], and ended on November 10, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/by-the-sea-filming-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt/|title=Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt's By the Sea Starts Filming Today|work=Collider|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-111014-star-wars-the-force-awakens-along-with-angelina-joliebrad-pitts-by-the-sea-wraps-more/|title=On the Set for 11/10/14: Star Wars: The Force Awakens Along with Angelina Jolie/Brad Pitt's By The Sea Wraps & More|work=ssninsider.com|accessdate=December 4, 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150313065041/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-111014-star-wars-the-force-awakens-along-with-angelina-joliebrad-pitts-by-the-sea-wraps-more/|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn May 2015, the film was slated for a November 13, 2015 release.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Angelina Jolie, Brad Pitt Movie 'By the Sea' Lands Awards Season Release Date|url=https://www.thewrap.com/angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-movie-by-the-sea-lands-awards-season-release-date/|accessdate=May 7, 2015|publisher=TheWrap.com|date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing and promotion===\nStills from the film were released on September 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Breznican|first1=Anthony|title=First Look: Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt swept away in romantic drama 'By the Sea'|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/09/15/first-look-angelina-jolie-and-brad-pitt-swept-away-by-the-sea-exclusive/|accessdate=September 17, 2014|publisher=ew.com|date=September 15, 2014}}</ref> On August 6, 2015, a teaser trailer for the film was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NJD6ZyADl8o |title=By the Sea TRAILER 1 (2015) - Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie Movie HD |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-08-06 |accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''By the Sea'' was released on DVD & Blu-ray in Australia and Germany on June 9, 2016, in the United Kingdom on June 20, 2016,<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sea-Blu-ray-Angelina-Jolie-Pitt/dp/B018K7LZ94/</ref> and in Canada and the United States on July 5, 2016.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''By the Sea'' opened theatrically in ten venues, earning $96,250, ranking number 38 in the domestic box office.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2015&wknd=46&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 13-15, 2015 | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | date=November 16, 2015 | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref> As of December 10, the film has grossed $538,460 in the United States and Canada, and $2,796,467 overseas for a worldwide total of $3,334,927.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bythesea.htm | title=By the Sea (2015) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed to negative reviews from critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 34%, based on 135 reviews, with an average rating of 4.8/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''By the Sea'' may intrigue celebrity voyeurs or fans of a certain type of [[Art film|arthouse cinema]], but for most viewers, its beauty won't be enough to offset its narrative inertia.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Justin|last=Chang|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/by_the_sea_2015/|title= By the Sea (2015) |website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 44 out of 100, based on 35 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/by-the-sea |title=By the Sea reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Justin Chang, chief film critic for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said: \"''By the Sea'' always offers something to tickle the eye and ear, even as it leaves the heart and mind coolly unstirred.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/by-the-sea-review-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-1201634877/|title='By the Sea' Review: Angelina Jolie Pitt, Brad Pitt Star in Marriage Drama|website=Variety.com|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3707106|By the Sea}}\n* {{Mojo title|bythesea|By the Sea}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|by_the_sea_2015|By the Sea}}\n* {{Metacritic film|by-the-sea|By the Sea}}\n\n{{Angelina Jolie}}\n{{Brad Pitt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:By The Sea (2015 Film)}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brad Pitt]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malta]]\n[[Category:Plan B Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = By the Sea\n| image = By The Sea Teaser.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Angelina Jolie|Angelina Jolie Pitt]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Angelina Jolie Pitt \n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n}}\n| writer = Angelina Jolie Pitt\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Brad Pitt\n* Angelina Jolie Pitt\n}}\n| music = [[Gabriel Yared]]\n| cinematography = [[Christian Berger]]\n| editing = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Martin Pensa]]\n* Patricia Rommel\n}}\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n*Jolie Pass\n*[[Plan B Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|05|[[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]]|2015|11|13|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:13--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sea-film-1 | title=''BY THE SEA'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 24, 2015 | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* French}}\n| budget = $10 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n| gross = $3.3 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''By the Sea''''' is a 2015 American [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Angelina Jolie Pitt]], and produced by and starring Jolie Pitt and [[Brad Pitt]]. Shot in August 2014 during Pitt and Jolie's [[honeymoon]] in [[Gozo]], [[Malta]], the film was released by [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] on November 13, 2015.\n\nThe film received mixed to negative reviews and was a [[box office bomb]], grossing just $3.3 million against its $10 million budget.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the 1960s, in France, an American couple, former dancer Vanessa and her husband Roland, a successful writer, have been married 14 years. They drive to a coastal hotel. Roland wants to write a story while staying there. The two are barely on speaking terms; Vanessa is withdrawn and grieving for an unknown reason. Roland appears to drink too much and seems unhappy that Vanessa is no longer interested in him sexually.\n\nRoland becomes friendly with the local cafe owner, an older man still grieving his much-loved late wife, but who carries on, cheerfully accepting what life has given him. Vanessa watches a local fisherman who goes out every day on the outgoing tide and returns on the incoming one, catching few fish, but contented.\n\nVanessa and Roland strike up a friendship with an attractive young couple staying in the room next to them. Soon after, they discover that the wall between their two rooms has a disused radiator pipe hole, enabling them to watch the couple in their bedroom talking and having sex.\n\nGradually their experiences at the hotel enable Vanessa and Roland to start patching up their relationship. However, Vanessa attempts a liaison with the young husband in the next room, interrupted violently by Roland, who has been watching through the wall. He bruises the husband, who must later explain to his wife and does so truthfully, seriously damaging the relationship between the young couple. This also triggers a confrontation between Vanessa and Roland, during which he tells her that if she wishes to hurt him, she should just go ahead and hurt him physically. Roland asserts that her seduction of the husband was motivated by his wife's envy of the young couple - particularly of their ability to bear children. Roland physically restrains Vanessa against a wall and makes her speak of herself being barren which they haven't been able to talk about. After a short struggle, Vanessa breaks down and weeps for her loss. Later, Roland explains to the young wife that two miscarriages caused Vanessa's lasting grief, withdrawal and behavior toward her husband.\n\nHaving finally come to terms with their life together, Vanessa seems able to go on and Roland is able to finish writing a new book. It seems also that the young couple next door may be able to work their way through the episode as well, and come out stronger on the other side.\n\nAs Vanessa and Roland leave the hotel and drive away, they appear to be reconciled.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Brad Pitt]] as Roland\n* [[Angelina Jolie Pitt]] as Vanessa\n* [[M\u00e9lanie Laurent]] as L\u00e9a\n* [[Niels Arestrup]] as Michel\n* [[Melvil Poupaud]] as Fran\u00e7ois\n* [[Richard Bohringer]] as Patrice\n\n==Production==\nIn May 2014, it was announced that Angelina Jolie Pitt would co-star with Brad Pitt in a film titled ''By the Sea'', to be written and directed by Jolie.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Universal Buys Angelina Jolie-Brad Pitt Pic Deadline Broke In May|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/universal-buys-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-pic-deadline-broke-in-may/|accessdate=July 19, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=July 18, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' speculated it would be a relationship drama that Jolie Pitt wrote several years ago, centering on a couple with issues who take a vacation in a last-ditch effort to save their marriage.\n\nThis was the first cinematic collaboration between the two since ''[[Mr. & Mrs. Smith (2005 film)|Mr. & Mrs. Smith]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brad-pitt-angelina-jolie-teaming-700953|title=Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie Teaming Up for Mystery Movie Project|date=May 2, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Joseph Muscat]] of [[Malta]] confirmed the project, stating that it would be partially filmed at [[M\u0121arr ix-Xini]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kauri|title=Brangelina are headed to Malta|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/07/14/brangelina-are-headed-to-malta/|accessdate=July 19, 2014|publisher=onlocationvacations.com|date=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20140703/local/angelina-jolie-and-brad-pitt-blockbuster-to-be-filmed-at-mgarr-ix-xini.526135|title=Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt blockbuster to be filmed at Mgarr ix-Xini - timesofmalta.com|work=Times of Malta|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJolie Pitt has stated that the film \"at its core, is about grief\" further noting that the loss of her mother in 2007 caused a great deal of sadness for her.<ref name=mom>{{cite web|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|title='By the Sea' Premiere: Angelina Jolie Pitt on Making a Movie For Her Mother|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/by-sea-premiere-angelina-jolie-837696|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> To that end, the movie resembles movies of the 1960s and '70s; Jolie Pitt stated that her mother \"loved films of that period\".<ref name=mom/>  [[Christian Berger]] is the cinematographer; he used mostly natural light throughout filming,<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood |first=Adam |url=https://collider.com/by-the-sea-images-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt/ |title=By the Sea Images Reveal Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt as a Married Couple |publisher=Collider |date=2014-09-15 |accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref> while [[Jon Hutman]] is the production designer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Caranicas|first1=Peter|title=Below the Line Bookings|url=https://variety.com/2014/artisans/news/below-the-line-bookings-7-1201319626/|accessdate=October 3, 2014|publisher=variety.com|date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] and production began on August 19, 2014, in [[Gozo]], [[Malta]], and ended on November 10, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/by-the-sea-filming-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt/|title=Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt's By the Sea Starts Filming Today|work=Collider|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-111014-star-wars-the-force-awakens-along-with-angelina-joliebrad-pitts-by-the-sea-wraps-more/|title=On the Set for 11/10/14: Star Wars: The Force Awakens Along with Angelina Jolie/Brad Pitt's By The Sea Wraps & More|work=ssninsider.com|accessdate=December 4, 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150313065041/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-111014-star-wars-the-force-awakens-along-with-angelina-joliebrad-pitts-by-the-sea-wraps-more/|archive-date=March 13, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn May 2015, the film was slated for a November 13, 2015 release.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Angelina Jolie, Brad Pitt Movie 'By the Sea' Lands Awards Season Release Date|url=https://www.thewrap.com/angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-movie-by-the-sea-lands-awards-season-release-date/|accessdate=May 7, 2015|publisher=TheWrap.com|date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing and promotion===\nStills from the film were released on September 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Breznican|first1=Anthony|title=First Look: Angelina Jolie and Brad Pitt swept away in romantic drama 'By the Sea'|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/09/15/first-look-angelina-jolie-and-brad-pitt-swept-away-by-the-sea-exclusive/|accessdate=September 17, 2014|publisher=ew.com|date=September 15, 2014}}</ref> On August 6, 2015, a teaser trailer for the film was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NJD6ZyADl8o |title=By the Sea TRAILER 1 (2015) - Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie Movie HD |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-08-06 |accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''By the Sea'' was released on DVD & Blu-ray in Australia and Germany on June 9, 2016, in the United Kingdom on June 20, 2016,<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sea-Blu-ray-Angelina-Jolie-Pitt/dp/B018K7LZ94/</ref> and in Canada and the United States on July 5, 2016.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''By the Sea'' opened theatrically in ten venues, earning $96,250, ranking number 38 in the domestic box office.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2015&wknd=46&p=.htm | title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 13-15, 2015 | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | date=November 16, 2015 | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref> As of December 10, the film has grossed $538,460 in the United States and Canada, and $2,796,467 overseas for a worldwide total of $3,334,927.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bythesea.htm | title=By the Sea (2015) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed to negative reviews from critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a rating of 34%, based on 135 reviews, with an average rating of 4.8/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''By the Sea'' may intrigue celebrity voyeurs or fans of a certain type of [[Art film|arthouse cinema]], but for most viewers, its beauty won't be enough to offset its narrative inertia.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Justin|last=Chang|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/by_the_sea_2015/|title= By the Sea (2015) |website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 44 out of 100, based on 35 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/by-the-sea |title=By the Sea reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Justin Chang, chief film critic for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said: \"''By the Sea'' always offers something to tickle the eye and ear, even as it leaves the heart and mind coolly unstirred.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/by-the-sea-review-angelina-jolie-brad-pitt-1201634877/|title='By the Sea' Review: Angelina Jolie Pitt, Brad Pitt Star in Marriage Drama|website=Variety.com|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 6, 2015|accessdate=July 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3707106|By the Sea}}\n* {{Mojo title|bythesea|By the Sea}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|by_the_sea_2015|By the Sea}}\n* {{Metacritic film|by-the-sea|By the Sea}}\n\n{{Angelina Jolie}}\n{{Brad Pitt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:By The Sea (2015 Film)}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brad Pitt]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malta]]\n[[Category:Plan B Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Angelina Jolie]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Julthep", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/By_the_Sea_(2015_film)"}
{"title_page": "Mount Whitney", "text_new": "{{about|the mountain|the former town with this name|Lone Pine Station, California|the ship|USS Mount Whitney (LCC-20)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Whitney\n| other_name = Fisherman's Peak, Tumanguya\n| photo = Mount Whitney 2003-03-25.jpg\n| photo_caption = [[East Face (Mount Whitney)|East Face]] close-up seen from the [[Whitney Portal]]\n| elevation_system = NAVD88\n| elevation_mi = 14410045\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=ngs/>\n| prominence_ft = 10,075\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=Peakbagger/>\n| isolation_mi = 1647\n| isolation_ref = <ref name=Peakbagger/>\n| parent_peak = [[Pico de Orizaba]]<ref name=Peakbagger_KeyCol/>\n| listing = {{unbulleted list\n|[[List of peaks by prominence|World's most prominent peaks]] 81st\n|[[Topographic isolation|World's most isolated peaks]] 18th\n|[[List of the highest major summits of North America|North America's highest peaks]] 24th\n|[[List of the most prominent summits of North America|North America's prominent peaks]] 16th\n|[[List of the most isolated major summits of North America|North America's isolated peaks]] 4th\n|[[List of U.S. states by elevation|U.S. state high point]] 2nd\n|[[List of the highest major summits of the United States|US highest major peaks]] 11th\n|[[List of highest mountain peaks of California|California's highest major peaks]] 1st\n|[[List of California fourteeners|California fourteeners]] 1st<ref name=\"pbl\">{{cite peakbagger |lid=21319 |name=California 14,000-foot Peaks |accessdate=2016-03-24}}</ref>\n|[[List of highest points in California by county|California county high points]] 1st\n|[[SPS Emblem]] peak<ref name=\"SPS\">{{cite sps}}</ref>\n|WSC Star peak<ref name=\"wsc\">{{cite wsc |accessdate=2016-03-24}}</ref>\n|[[Ultra-prominent peak|Ultra]]\n}}\n| location = [[Sequoia National Park]] / [[Inyo National Forest]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| map = USA California#USA\n| map_caption = Location in California, U.S.\n| map_size = 220\n| label_position = left\n| range = [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|36.578580925|N|118.29199495|W|type:mountain_region:US-CA_scale:100000_source:NGS|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=\"ngs\"/>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Mount Whitney\n| type = [[Granite]]\n| age = [[Cretaceous]]\n| first_ascent = August 18, 1873 by Charles Begole, Albert Johnson, and John Lucas<ref name=\"Farquhar\"/>\n| easiest_route = [[Mount Whitney Trail]] ({{YDS|1}})\n}}\n'''Mount Whitney''' is the tallest mountain in the [[contiguous United States]] and the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]], with an elevation of {{convert|4421|m||order=flip}}.<ref name=\"ngs\"/> It is located in [[Eastern California|East]]\u2013[[Central California]], on the boundary between California's [[Inyo County, California|Inyo]] and [[Tulare County, California|Tulare]] counties, {{convert|84.6|mi}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcc.gov/media/radio/distance-and-azimuths|title=Find Distance and Azimuths Between 2 Sets of Coordinates|publisher=Federal Communications Commission|quote=Coordinates of Mount Whitney = 36.578581, -118.291995 and Badwater Basin = 36.250278, -116.825833|accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref> west-northwest of the lowest point in North America at [[Badwater Basin]] in [[Death Valley National Park]] at {{convert|282|ft|abbr=on}} below sea level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/deva/faqs.htm|title=Death Valley National Park, Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=National Park Service|quote=Badwater Basin-282 feet below sea level...the lowest in North America.|accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref> The west slope of the mountain is in [[Sequoia National Park]] and the summit is the southern terminus of the [[John Muir Trail]] which runs {{convert|211.9|mi|km|1|abbr=on}} from [[Happy Isles]] in [[Yosemite Valley]].<ref name=YOSE>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/yose/planyourvisit/jmt.htm |title=John Muir and Pacific Crest Trails |editor=NPS |accessdate=2015-05-07}}</ref> The east slope is in the [[Inyo National Forest]] in [[Inyo County]].\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:A347, Skypilot near summit of Mount Whitney, California, USA, 2011.JPG|thumb|left|[[Polemonium eximium|Sky pilot]] blooming on ridge just below summit]]\nThe summit of Mount Whitney is on the [[Sierra Crest]] and the [[Great Basin Divide]]. It lies near many of the highest peaks of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]].<ref name=Sierra>{{cite web|url=http://climbing.about.com/od/mountainclimbing/a/MtWhitneyFacts.htm |title=Mount Whitney: Highest Mountain in California |editor=about sports |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref> The peak rises dramatically above the [[Owens Valley]], sitting {{convert|10778|ft}} or just over two miles above the town of [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]] 15 miles to the east, in the [[Owens Valley]].<ref name=Sierra/> It rises more gradually on the west side, lying only about {{convert|3000|ft}} above the John Muir Trail at Guitar Lake.<ref name=Guitar>{{cite web|url=http://www.everytrail.com/guide/the-high-sierra-trail-segment-7-of-7/map |title=Trail Map of The High Sierra Trail: Segment 7 of 7 California |editor=Everytrail.com |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref>\n\nThe mountain is partially dome-shaped, with its famously jagged ridges extending to the sides.<ref name=\"backpacker\">{{cite journal|last1=Perlman|first1=Eric|title=Nice Going, Whitney|journal=Backpager|date=May 1985|pages=49\u201355|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UuADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=whitney+jagged+and+smoorh#v=onepage&q=whitney%20jagged%20and%20smoorh&f=true|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref> Mount Whitney is above the [[tree line]] and has an [[alpine climate]] and [[alpine tundra|ecology]].<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite book|last1=Joyce|first1=Quinn (ed)|title=Earth's Landscape: An Encyclopedia of the World's Geographic Features [2 volumes]|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1610694465|pages=511\u2013512|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ErkxBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA511&lpg=PA511&dq=tree+line+alpine+climate+Whitney#v=onepage&q=tree%20line%20alpine%20climate%20Whitney&f=false|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref> Very few plants grow near the summit: one example is the [[Polemonium eximium|sky pilot]], a [[cushion plant]] that grows low to the ground.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\">\n  {{cite book\n  | last = Schoenherr\n  | first = Allan A.\n  | title = A Natural History of California\n  | year = 1995\n  | publisher = [[University of California Press]]\n  | isbn = 0-520-06922-6\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/naturalhistoryof00scho\n  }}</ref>\nThe only animals are transient, such as the butterfly ''[[Parnassius phoebus]]'' and the [[grey-crowned rosy finch|gray-crowned rosy finch]].<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/>\n\n=== Hydrology ===\nThe mountain is the highest point on the [[Great Basin Divide]]. Waterways on the west side of the peak flow into Whitney Creek, which flows into the [[Kern River]]. The Kern River terminates at [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] in the [[Tulare Lake|Tulare Basin]], the southern part of the [[San Joaquin Valley]]. During very wet years, water overflows from the Tulare Basin into the [[San Joaquin River]] which flows to the Pacific Ocean. From the east, water from Mount Whitney flows to Lone Pine Creek, which joins the [[Owens River]], which in turn terminates at [[Owens Lake]], an endorheic lake of the [[Great Basin]].\n\n=== Elevation measurements ===\nThe estimated elevation of the summit of Mount Whitney has changed over the years. The technology of elevation measurement has become more refined and, more importantly, the vertical coordinate system has changed. The peak was commonly said to be at {{convert|14494|ft|abbr=on}} and this is the elevation stamped on the USGS brass benchmark disk on the summit.  An older plaque on the summit (sheet metal with black lettering on white enamel) reads \"elevation 14,496.811 feet\" but this was estimated using the older [[geodetic system|vertical datum]] ([[Sea Level Datum of 1929|NGVD29]]) from 1929. Since then the shape of the [[Earth]] (the [[geoid]]) has been estimated more accurately. Using a new vertical datum established in 1988 ([[North American Vertical Datum of 1988|NAVD88]]) the benchmark is now estimated to be at {{convert|14505|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ngs\"/><ref name=ngs_hcm/>\n\n== Geology ==\n[[Image:Sierra nevada schematic.svg|thumb|left|Schematic of Sierra Nevada [[fault block]]]]\nThe eastern slope of Whitney is far steeper than its western slope because the entire Sierra Nevada is the result of a [[fault block]] that is analogous to a cellar door: the door is hinged on the west and is slowly rising on the east.<ref name=usfs_sn/>\n\nThe rise is caused by a [[Fault (geology)|fault]] system that runs along the eastern base of the Sierra, below Mount Whitney. Thus, the [[granite]] that forms Mount Whitney is the same as the granite that forms the [[Alabama Hills]], thousands of feet lower down.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/> The raising of Whitney (and the downdrop of the Owens Valley) is due to the same geological forces that cause the [[Basin and Range Province]]: the crust of much of the intermontane west is slowly being stretched.<ref name=\"nps\">\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.nps.gov/grba/planyourvisit/the-great-basin.htm\n  | title = The Great Basin|work=Great Basin National Park\n  | publisher = [[National Park Service|US National Park Service]]\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe granite that forms Mount Whitney is part of the [[Sierra Nevada Batholith]].<ref name=\"mcphee\">{{cite book|last1=McPhee|first1=John|title=Annals of a Former World|date=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=0374708460|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GS81F0RNxesC&pg=PT503&dq=batholith.+In+Cretaceous+subduction+Whitney++granite.#v=onepage&q=batholith.%20In%20Cretaceous%20subduction%20Whitney%20%20granite.&f=false | accessdate = 2016-05-08 }}</ref> In [[Cretaceous]] time, masses of molten rock that originated from [[subduction]] rose underneath what is now Whitney and solidified underground to form large expanses of granite.<ref name=\"mcphee\"/> In the last 2 to 10 million years, the Sierra was pushed up which enabled glacial and river erosion to strip the upper layers of rock to reveal the resistant granite that makes up Mount Whitney today.<ref name=\"stephen\">{{cite book|last1=Whitney|first1=Stephen|title=A Sierra Club naturalist's guide to the Sierra Nevada|date=1979|publisher=Sierra Club Books|isbn=0871562154|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WuATAQAAIAAJ&q=2+to+10+million+years+Whitney&dq=2+to+10+million+years+Whitney|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nThe summit of Mount Whitney has an alpine tundra climate (''ET'') under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. The climate table contains [[Interpolation|interpolated]] data for an area below the summit. \n\nSummer temperatures at the top are highly variable, ranging from below freezing to highs near {{convert|80|F|C}} during extreme heat waves in the Owens Valley.\n\nWinter [[snowpack]] will be much greater than the liquid precipitation figures shown here. Based on the range from the highest average high of {{cvt|25.7|F}} to the lowest average low of {{cvt|4.2|F}} for winter temperatures in the table (December through March), every {{convert|1|in}} of liquid precipitation equates to approximately {{convert|15-40|in}} of snow, with lower temperatures producing the greater snow depths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/attachments/Estimating_the_Water_Equivalent_of_Snow.pdf |title=Estimating the Water Equivalent of Snow |website=ncdc.noaa.gov |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] |page=3 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location=Latitude: 36.5786, Longitude: -118.2920, Elevation: 13346ft (4068m) \u2014 30-year normals, 1981-2010\n|width=auto\n|single line=yes\n|Jan precipitation inch = 7.75\n|Feb precipitation inch = 7.44\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.26\n|Apr precipitation inch = 3.33\n|May precipitation inch = 1.79\n|Jun precipitation inch = 0.98\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.97\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.77\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.00\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.79\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.27\n|Dec precipitation inch = 6.54\n|year precipitation inch = 41.9\n|Jan low F = 6.1\n|Feb low F = 4.2\n|Mar low F = 5.6\n|Apr low F = 8.6\n|May low F = 16.9\n|Jun low F = 26.1\n|Jul low F = 33.3\n|Aug low F = 31.7\n|Sep low F = 26.4\n|Oct low F = 19.2\n|Nov low F = 11.7\n|Dec low F = 6.9\n|year low F = 16.4\n|Jan mean F = 15.0\n|Feb mean F = 13.7\n|Mar mean F = 15.6\n|Apr mean F = 20.0\n|May mean F = 27.9\n|Jun mean F = 36.9\n|Jul mean F = 43.7\n|Aug mean F = 42.7\n|Sep mean F = 37.3\n|Oct mean F = 29.9\n|Nov mean F = 20.9\n|Dec mean F = 15.2\n|year mean F = 26.6\n|Jan high F = 23.9\n|Feb high F = 23.2\n|Mar high F = 25.7\n|Apr high F = 31.4\n|May high F = 38.9\n|Jun high F = 47.7\n|Jul high F = 54.1\n|Aug high F = 53.7\n|Sep high F = 48.2\n|Oct high F = 40.6\n|Nov high F = 30.2\n|Dec high F = 23.5\n|year high F = 41111\n|source=PRISM Climate Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prism.oregonstate.edu/explorer/|title=30-year normals, 1981-2010, 800m PRISM cells / interpolated|publisher=PRISM Climate Group, Oregon State University|quote=To find the table data on the PRISM website, start by clicking ''Coordinates'' (under ''Location''); copy ''Latitude'' and ''Longitude figures'' from top of table; click ''Zoom to location''; click ''Precipitation, Minimum temp, Mean temp, Maximum temp''; click ''30-year normals, 1981-2010''; click ''800m''; click ''Interpolate grid cell values''; click ''Retrieve Time Series'' button.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Exploration history ==\n[[File:Mount Whitney from south.jpg|thumb|left|Mount Whitney as seen from [[Mount Langley]]]]\nIn July 1864, the members of the [[California Geological Survey]] named the peak after [[Josiah Whitney]], the State Geologist of [[California]] and benefactor of the survey.<ref name=\"Farquhar\"/> During the same expedition, geologist [[Clarence King]] attempted to climb Whitney from its west side, but stopped just short. In 1871, King returned to climb what he believed to be Whitney, but having taken a different approach, he actually summited nearby [[Mount Langley]]. Upon learning of his mistake in 1873, King finally completed his own first ascent of Whitney, but did so a month too late to claim the first recorded ascent.<ref name=\"King\">{{cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Clarence\n  | authorlink = Clarence King\n  | title = Mountaineering in the Sierra Nevada\n  | url = http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/mountaineering_in_the_sierra_nevada/\n  | accessdate = 2009-02-01\n  | edition = 10th\n  | origyear = 1872\n  | year = 1902\n  | chapter = Chapter XIII Mount Whitney\n  | chapterurl = http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/mountaineering_in_the_sierra_nevada/13.html\n  | isbn = 0-585-27432-0 }}</ref> Just a month earlier, on August 18, 1873, Charles Begole, A. H. Johnson, and John Lucas, all of nearby [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]], had become the first to reach the highest summit in the contiguous United States. As they climbed the mountain during a fishing trip to nearby Kern Canyon, they called the mountain Fisherman's Peak.<ref name=\"Farquhar\"/>\n\nIn 1881 [[Samuel Pierpont Langley]], founder of the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] remained for some time on the summit, making daily observations on the solar heat.<ref name=ea>{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Whitney, Mount}}</ref> Accompanying Langley in 1881 was another party consisting of Judge William B. Wallace of Visalia, W. A. Wright and Reverend Frederick Wales.<ref name=\"seq\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.sequoiaparksfoundation.org/2012/historic-people-and-places-william-b-wallace/\n |accessdate  = 2015-10-04\n |title       = Historic People And Places: WILLIAM B. WALLACE\n |publisher   = Sequoia Parks Foundation\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120904001136/http://www.sequoiaparksfoundation.org/2012/historic-people-and-places-william-b-wallace/\n |archivedate = 2012-09-04\n}}</ref> Wallace later wrote in his memoirs<ref name = \"paiute\">\n  {{cite book\n  | last = Wallace\n  | first = William B.\n  | chapter = A Night On Mt. Whitney\n  | title = Mt. Whitney Club Journal\n  | year = 1902\n  | volume = 1\n  | issue = 1\n  | pages = 8\u20139\n  | publisher = Mt. Whitney Club\n  | location = Visalia, CA\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=Q35LAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=\"Too-man-i-goo-yah\"#v=onepage&q=\"Too-man-i-goo-yah\"&f=false }}\n</ref> that \"The [[Northern Paiute| Pi Ute [Paiute] ]] Indians called Mt. Whitney \"''Too-man-i-goo-yah'',\" which means \"the very old man.\" They believe that the Great Spirit who presides over the destiny of their people once had his home in that mountain.\"  The spelling ''Too-man-i-goo-yah'' is a transliteration from the indigenous Paiute [[Mono language (California)|Mono language]]. Other variations are ''Too-man-go-yah''<ref name = \"14ers\">\n  {{cite book\n  | title = Climbing California's Fourteeners: The Route Guide to the Fifteen Highest Peaks\n  | first1 = Stephen\n  | last1 = Porcella\n  | first2 = Cameron\n  | last2 = Burns\n  | publisher = [[The Mountaineers (club)#Mountaineers Books|Mountaineers Books]]\n  | page = 55\n  | isbn = 0-89886-555-7\n  | date = 1998\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=uM6amm4BDtAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Climbing+California's+Fourteeners:#v=onepage&q=too%20man&f=false}}\n</ref> and  ''Tumanguya''.<ref name = \"bustle\">\n {{ cite web\n  | url = http://www.bustle.com/articles/107621-5-whitewashed-american-landmarks-that-like-mount-mckinley-sorely-need-a-name-change\n  | website = www.bustle.com\n  |  title = 5 Whitewashed American Landmarks That, Like Mount McKinley, Sorely Need A Name Change\n  | first = Lauren\n  | last = Barbato\n  | date = 2015-08-31  }}\n</ref>\n\n[[File:Smithsonian Hut Whitney.jpg|thumb|The [[Smithsonian Institution Shelter]] on Whitney's summit]]\nIn 1891, the [[United States Geological Survey]]'s Board on Geographic Names decided to recognize the earlier name Mount Whitney.  Despite losing out on their preferred name, residents of Lone Pine financed the first trail to the summit, engineered by Gustave Marsh, and completed on July 22, 1904. Just four days later, the new trail enabled the first recorded death on Whitney. Having hiked the trail, [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|U.S. Bureau of Fisheries]] employee Byrd Surby was struck and killed by lightning while eating lunch on the exposed summit. In response to this event, Marsh began work on the stone hut that would become the [[Smithsonian Institution Shelter]], and completed it in 1909.<ref name=\"LPC\">\n  {{cite web\n |url=http://www.lonepinechamber.org/history/whitneyhist2.html\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211171515/http://www.lonepinechamber.org/history/whitneyhist2.html\n |archivedate=2012-02-11\n |work=Mount Whitney History\n |title=Mt. Whitney's Early Days\n |publisher=Lone Pine Chamber of Commerce\n |accessdate=2009-02-01\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nA movement began after [[World War&nbsp;II]] to rename the mountain for [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis |id=269051 |name=Mount Whitney |accessdate=2009-02-01}}</ref>  However, the name Mount Whitney has persisted.\n\n==Climbing routes==\n\n=== Trails ===\n[[File:Whitney trail at night.jpg|thumb|Long-exposure photograph of hikers ascending before sunrise]]\nThe most popular route to the summit is by way of the [[Mount Whitney Trail]] which starts at [[Whitney Portal]], at an elevation of {{convert|8360|ft|abbr=on}}, {{convert|13|mi|abbr=on}} west of the town of [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]].  The hike is about {{convert|22|mi|km|abbr=on}} round trip with an elevation gain of over {{convert|6100|ft|abbr=on}}. Permits are required year round, and to prevent overuse a limited number of permits are issued by the [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] between May 1 and November 1.<ref>\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/inyo/recreation/wild/mtwhitney.shtml\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080414042448/http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/inyo/recreation/wild/mtwhitney.shtml\n  | archivedate = 2008-04-14\n  | title = Recreational Activities - Mt. Whitney\n  | publisher = US Forest Service\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-09 }}</ref> The Forest Service holds an annual lottery for hiking and backpacking permits on the Mount Whitney Trail. Applications are accepted from February 1 through March 15. Any permits left over after the lottery is completed typically go on sale April 1. Most hikers plan to stay one or two nights camping along the route.<ref>\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/inyo/passes-permits/recreation/?cid=stelprdb5150055\n  | title = Mount Whitney Lottery - Permit Reservations\n  | publisher = US Forest Service\n  | accessdate = 2014-01-23 }}</ref> Those in good physical condition sometimes attempt to reach the summit and return to Whitney Portal in one day. A single day hike requires a \"day use\" permit that prohibits the use of overnight camping gear (sleeping bag and tent). Day hikers often leave Whitney Portal before sunrise and hike from 12 to 18 hours round trip.<ref name=dayhiker/>\n\nLonger approaches to Whitney arrive at its west side, connecting to the Mount Whitney Trail near the summit by way of the [[John Muir Trail]].\n\n=== Scrambles ===\n[[File:Mt. Whitney and south-eastern Sierra Nevada aerial.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Mount Whitney and the steep eastern side of the Sierra Nevada, from the north]]\nThe \"Mountaineer's Route\", a gully on the north side of the east face first climbed by [[John Muir]], is considered a [[scrambling|scramble]], {{YDS|3}} ([[Grade (climbing)#International French Adjectival System (IFAS)|PD+]]).<ref name=\"Secor\">{{cite Secor |pages=70\u201375}}</ref> The fastest recorded time up this route to the summit and back to the portal is 3 hours 10 minutes, by Jason Lakey of Bishop.<ref name=rockice/>\n\n=== Technical climbs ===\nThe steep eastern side of the mountain offers a variety of [[climbing]] challenges. The [[East Face (Mount Whitney)|East Face]] route, first climbed in 1931, is one of the ''[[Fifty Classic Climbs of North America]]'' [[climbing route|route]]s and involves technical [[free climbing]] ({{YDS|5.7}}) but is mostly class 4.  Other routes range up to grade 5.10d.<ref name=\"Secor\"/>\n\nSouth of the main summit there are a series of minor summits that are completely inconspicuous from the west but appear as a series of \"needles\" from the east. The routes on these include some of the finest big-wall climbing in the high Sierra. Two of the needles were named after participants in an 1880 scientific expedition to the mountain. Keeler Needle was named for [[James Edward Keeler|James Keeler]] and Day Needle was named for William Cathcart Day. The latter has now been renamed Crooks Peak after [[Hulda Crooks]] who hiked up Mount Whitney every year until well into her nineties.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Mountains|California}}}}\n* [[List of mountain peaks of California]]\n* [[List of highest points in California by county]]\n* [[List of U.S. states by elevation]]\n* [[List of the highest major summits of the United States]]\n* [[List of the most prominent summits of the United States]]\n* [[List of the most isolated major summits of the United States]]\n* [[Whitney Classic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=dayhiker>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.dayhiker.com/directory/MtWhitney.htm|title=Mt. Whitney \u2013 One Day Hike\n   |publisher=dayhiker.com |accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Farquhar\">\n  {{cite book |last=Farquhar |first=Francis P. |authorlink=Francis P. Farquhar\n  |title=Place Names of the High Sierra\n  |url=http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/place_names_of_the_high_sierra/w.html\n  |accessdate=2007-08-12 |publisher=[[Sierra Club]]\n  |location=[[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]\n  |year=1926}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ngs\">\n  {{cite ngs |id=GT1811 |name=Whitney |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n<ref name=ngs_hcm>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.ngs.noaa.gov/TOOLS/Vertcon/vert_method.html\n  |title=Height Conversion Methodology |publisher=U.S. National Geodetic Survey\n  |accessdate=2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Peakbagger\">\n  {{cite peakbagger |pid=2829|name=Mount Whitney, California |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Peakbagger_KeyCol\">\n  {{cite peakbagger |kid=2829|name=Playas Valley/Pride Draw Saddle |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=rockice>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.rockandice.com/news/1272-bishop-local-adds-513b-crack-and-speed-solos-whitney-region\n  |title=Bishop Local Adds 5.13b Crack, And Speed Solos Whitney Region\n  |publisher=Rock and Ice |date=December 9, 2010\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212234615/http://www.rockandice.com/news/1272-bishop-local-adds-513b-crack-and-speed-solos-whitney-region\n  |archivedate=2010-12-12}}</ref>\n<ref name=usfs_sn>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/projects/ecoregions/m261e.htm\n  |title=Sierra Nevada\n  |work=Ecological Subregions of California\n  |publisher=[[United States Forest Service|US Forest Service]]\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601101102/http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/projects/ecoregions/m261e.htm\n  |archivedate=2008-06-01\n  |accessdate=2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Doug\n  | author2=Elisabeth Newbold\n  | title = Mount Whitney: Mountain Lore from the Whitney Store\n  | publisher = Westwind Publishing Company\n  | year = 1997\n  | isbn =  978-0-9653596-0-3 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons and category|Mount Whitney}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Mount Whitney}}\n\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recarea/?recid=20806\n  |title=Mt. Whitney Trail\n  |publisher=Inyo National Forest}}\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.whitneyzone.com/wz/\n  |title=Mt Whitney Hikers Association\n  |accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.whitneyportalstore.com\n  |title=Whitney Portal Store}}\n* {{cite summitpost |id=150227 |name=Mount Whitney}}\n* {{cite NIE |title=Whitney, Mount |year=1905}}\n\n{{NA highest}}{{NA prominent}}{{NA isolated}}\n{{California highest}}\n{{California Fourteeners}}\n{{U.S. State Highest Points}}\n{{Sequoia National Park}}\n{{California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitney, Mount}}\n[[Category:Fourteeners of California]]\n[[Category:Highest points of U.S. states]]\n[[Category:Inyo National Forest]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Inyo County, California]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Sequoia National Park]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the John Muir Wilderness]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Tulare County, California]]\n[[Category:Symbols of California]]\n[[Category:Highest points of United States national parks]]\n[[Category:North American 4000 m summits|Mount Whitney]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Northern California]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the mountain|the former town with this name|Lone Pine Station, California|the ship|USS Mount Whitney (LCC-20)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Mount Whitney\n| other_name = Fisherman's Peak, Tumanguya\n| photo = Mount Whitney 2003-03-25.jpg\n| photo_caption = [[East Face (Mount Whitney)|East Face]] close-up seen from the [[Whitney Portal]]\n| elevation_system = NAVD88\n| elevation_ft = 14505\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=ngs/>\n| prominence_ft = 10,075\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=Peakbagger/>\n| isolation_mi = 1647\n| isolation_ref = <ref name=Peakbagger/>\n| parent_peak = [[Pico de Orizaba]]<ref name=Peakbagger_KeyCol/>\n| listing = {{unbulleted list\n|[[List of peaks by prominence|World's most 