> It is located in [[Eastern California|East]]\u2013[[Central California]], on the boundary between California's [[Inyo County, California|Inyo]] and [[Tulare County, California|Tulare]] counties, {{convert|84.6|mi}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcc.gov/media/radio/distance-and-azimuths|title=Find Distance and Azimuths Between 2 Sets of Coordinates|publisher=Federal Communications Commission|quote=Coordinates of Mount Whitney = 36.578581, -118.291995 and Badwater Basin = 36.250278, -116.825833|accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref> west-northwest of the lowest point in North America at [[Badwater Basin]] in [[Death Valley National Park]] at {{convert|282|ft|abbr=on}} below sea level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/deva/faqs.htm|title=Death Valley National Park, Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=National Park Service|quote=Badwater Basin-282 feet below sea level...the lowest in North America.|accessdate=2016-12-21}}</ref> The west slope of the mountain is in [[Sequoia National Park]] and the summit is the southern terminus of the [[John Muir Trail]] which runs {{convert|211.9|mi|km|1|abbr=on}} from [[Happy Isles]] in [[Yosemite Valley]].<ref name=YOSE>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/yose/planyourvisit/jmt.htm |title=John Muir and Pacific Crest Trails |editor=NPS |accessdate=2015-05-07}}</ref> The east slope is in the [[Inyo National Forest]] in [[Inyo County]].\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:A347, Skypilot near summit of Mount Whitney, California, USA, 2011.JPG|thumb|left|[[Polemonium eximium|Sky pilot]] blooming on ridge just below summit]]\nThe summit of Mount Whitney is on the [[Sierra Crest]] and the [[Great Basin Divide]]. It lies near many of the highest peaks of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]].<ref name=Sierra>{{cite web|url=http://climbing.about.com/od/mountainclimbing/a/MtWhitneyFacts.htm |title=Mount Whitney: Highest Mountain in California |editor=about sports |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref> The peak rises dramatically above the [[Owens Valley]], sitting {{convert|10778|ft}} or just over two miles above the town of [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]] 15 miles to the east, in the [[Owens Valley]].<ref name=Sierra/> It rises more gradually on the west side, lying only about {{convert|3000|ft}} above the John Muir Trail at Guitar Lake.<ref name=Guitar>{{cite web|url=http://www.everytrail.com/guide/the-high-sierra-trail-segment-7-of-7/map |title=Trail Map of The High Sierra Trail: Segment 7 of 7 California |editor=Everytrail.com |accessdate=2015-05-08}}</ref>\n\nThe mountain is partially dome-shaped, with its famously jagged ridges extending to the sides.<ref name=\"backpacker\">{{cite journal|last1=Perlman|first1=Eric|title=Nice Going, Whitney|journal=Backpager|date=May 1985|pages=49\u201355|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UuADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=whitney+jagged+and+smoorh#v=onepage&q=whitney%20jagged%20and%20smoorh&f=true|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref> Mount Whitney is above the [[tree line]] and has an [[alpine climate]] and [[alpine tundra|ecology]].<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite book|last1=Joyce|first1=Quinn (ed)|title=Earth's Landscape: An Encyclopedia of the World's Geographic Features [2 volumes]|date=2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1610694465|pages=511\u2013512|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ErkxBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA511&lpg=PA511&dq=tree+line+alpine+climate+Whitney#v=onepage&q=tree%20line%20alpine%20climate%20Whitney&f=false|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref> Very few plants grow near the summit: one example is the [[Polemonium eximium|sky pilot]], a [[cushion plant]] that grows low to the ground.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\">\n  {{cite book\n  | last = Schoenherr\n  | first = Allan A.\n  | title = A Natural History of California\n  | year = 1995\n  | publisher = [[University of California Press]]\n  | isbn = 0-520-06922-6\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/naturalhistoryof00scho\n  }}</ref>\nThe only animals are transient, such as the butterfly ''[[Parnassius phoebus]]'' and the [[grey-crowned rosy finch|gray-crowned rosy finch]].<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/>\n\n=== Hydrology ===\nThe mountain is the highest point on the [[Great Basin Divide]]. Waterways on the west side of the peak flow into Whitney Creek, which flows into the [[Kern River]]. The Kern River terminates at [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] in the [[Tulare Lake|Tulare Basin]], the southern part of the [[San Joaquin Valley]]. During very wet years, water overflows from the Tulare Basin into the [[San Joaquin River]] which flows to the Pacific Ocean. From the east, water from Mount Whitney flows to Lone Pine Creek, which joins the [[Owens River]], which in turn terminates at [[Owens Lake]], an endorheic lake of the [[Great Basin]].\n\n=== Elevation measurements ===\nThe estimated elevation of the summit of Mount Whitney has changed over the years. The technology of elevation measurement has become more refined and, more importantly, the vertical coordinate system has changed. The peak was commonly said to be at {{convert|14494|ft|abbr=on}} and this is the elevation stamped on the USGS brass benchmark disk on the summit.  An older plaque on the summit (sheet metal with black lettering on white enamel) reads \"elevation 14,496.811 feet\" but this was estimated using the older [[geodetic system|vertical datum]] ([[Sea Level Datum of 1929|NGVD29]]) from 1929. Since then the shape of the [[Earth]] (the [[geoid]]) has been estimated more accurately. Using a new vertical datum established in 1988 ([[North American Vertical Datum of 1988|NAVD88]]) the benchmark is now estimated to be at {{convert|14505|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ngs\"/><ref name=ngs_hcm/>\n\n== Geology ==\n[[Image:Sierra nevada schematic.svg|thumb|left|Schematic of Sierra Nevada [[fault block]]]]\nThe eastern slope of Whitney is far steeper than its western slope because the entire Sierra Nevada is the result of a [[fault block]] that is analogous to a cellar door: the door is hinged on the west and is slowly rising on the east.<ref name=usfs_sn/>\n\nThe rise is caused by a [[Fault (geology)|fault]] system that runs along the eastern base of the Sierra, below Mount Whitney. Thus, the [[granite]] that forms Mount Whitney is the same as the granite that forms the [[Alabama Hills]], thousands of feet lower down.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/> The raising of Whitney (and the downdrop of the Owens Valley) is due to the same geological forces that cause the [[Basin and Range Province]]: the crust of much of the intermontane west is slowly being stretched.<ref name=\"nps\">\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.nps.gov/grba/planyourvisit/the-great-basin.htm\n  | title = The Great Basin|work=Great Basin National Park\n  | publisher = [[National Park Service|US National Park Service]]\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe granite that forms Mount Whitney is part of the [[Sierra Nevada Batholith]].<ref name=\"mcphee\">{{cite book|last1=McPhee|first1=John|title=Annals of a Former World|date=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=0374708460|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GS81F0RNxesC&pg=PT503&dq=batholith.+In+Cretaceous+subduction+Whitney++granite.#v=onepage&q=batholith.%20In%20Cretaceous%20subduction%20Whitney%20%20granite.&f=false | accessdate = 2016-05-08 }}</ref> In [[Cretaceous]] time, masses of molten rock that originated from [[subduction]] rose underneath what is now Whitney and solidified underground to form large expanses of granite.<ref name=\"mcphee\"/> In the last 2 to 10 million years, the Sierra was pushed up which enabled glacial and river erosion to strip the upper layers of rock to reveal the resistant granite that makes up Mount Whitney today.<ref name=\"stephen\">{{cite book|last1=Whitney|first1=Stephen|title=A Sierra Club naturalist's guide to the Sierra Nevada|date=1979|publisher=Sierra Club Books|isbn=0871562154|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WuATAQAAIAAJ&q=2+to+10+million+years+Whitney&dq=2+to+10+million+years+Whitney|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nThe summit of Mount Whitney has an alpine tundra climate (''ET'') under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. The climate table contains [[Interpolation|interpolated]] data for an area below the summit. \n\nSummer temperatures at the top are highly variable, ranging from below freezing to highs near {{convert|80|F|C}} during extreme heat waves in the Owens Valley.\n\nWinter [[snowpack]] will be much greater than the liquid precipitation figures shown here. Based on the range from the highest average high of {{cvt|25.7|F}} to the lowest average low of {{cvt|4.2|F}} for winter temperatures in the table (December through March), every {{convert|1|in}} of liquid precipitation equates to approximately {{convert|15-40|in}} of snow, with lower temperatures producing the greater snow depths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/attachments/Estimating_the_Water_Equivalent_of_Snow.pdf |title=Estimating the Water Equivalent of Snow |website=ncdc.noaa.gov |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] |page=3 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location=Latitude: 36.5786, Longitude: -118.2920, Elevation: 13346ft (4068m) \u2014 30-year normals, 1981-2010\n|width=auto\n|single line=yes\n|Jan precipitation inch = 7.75\n|Feb precipitation inch = 7.44\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.26\n|Apr precipitation inch = 3.33\n|May precipitation inch = 1.79\n|Jun precipitation inch = 0.98\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.97\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.77\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.00\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.79\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.27\n|Dec precipitation inch = 6.54\n|year precipitation inch = 41.9\n|Jan low F = 6.1\n|Feb low F = 4.2\n|Mar low F = 5.6\n|Apr low F = 8.6\n|May low F = 16.9\n|Jun low F = 26.1\n|Jul low F = 33.3\n|Aug low F = 31.7\n|Sep low F = 26.4\n|Oct low F = 19.2\n|Nov low F = 11.7\n|Dec low F = 6.9\n|year low F = 16.4\n|Jan mean F = 15.0\n|Feb mean F = 13.7\n|Mar mean F = 15.6\n|Apr mean F = 20.0\n|May mean F = 27.9\n|Jun mean F = 36.9\n|Jul mean F = 43.7\n|Aug mean F = 42.7\n|Sep mean F = 37.3\n|Oct mean F = 29.9\n|Nov mean F = 20.9\n|Dec mean F = 15.2\n|year mean F = 26.6\n|Jan high F = 23.9\n|Feb high F = 23.2\n|Mar high F = 25.7\n|Apr high F = 31.4\n|May high F = 38.9\n|Jun high F = 47.7\n|Jul high F = 54.1\n|Aug high F = 53.7\n|Sep high F = 48.2\n|Oct high F = 40.6\n|Nov high F = 30.2\n|Dec high F = 23.5\n|year high F = 36.8\n|source=PRISM Climate Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prism.oregonstate.edu/explorer/|title=30-year normals, 1981-2010, 800m PRISM cells / interpolated|publisher=PRISM Climate Group, Oregon State University|quote=To find the table data on the PRISM website, start by clicking ''Coordinates'' (under ''Location''); copy ''Latitude'' and ''Longitude figures'' from top of table; click ''Zoom to location''; click ''Precipitation, Minimum temp, Mean temp, Maximum temp''; click ''30-year normals, 1981-2010''; click ''800m''; click ''Interpolate grid cell values''; click ''Retrieve Time Series'' button.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Exploration history ==\n[[File:Mount Whitney from south.jpg|thumb|left|Mount Whitney as seen from [[Mount Langley]]]]\nIn July 1864, the members of the [[California Geological Survey]] named the peak after [[Josiah Whitney]], the State Geologist of [[California]] and benefactor of the survey.<ref name=\"Farquhar\"/> During the same expedition, geologist [[Clarence King]] attempted to climb Whitney from its west side, but stopped just short. In 1871, King returned to climb what he believed to be Whitney, but having taken a different approach, he actually summited nearby [[Mount Langley]]. Upon learning of his mistake in 1873, King finally completed his own first ascent of Whitney, but did so a month too late to claim the first recorded ascent.<ref name=\"King\">{{cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Clarence\n  | authorlink = Clarence King\n  | title = Mountaineering in the Sierra Nevada\n  | url = http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/mountaineering_in_the_sierra_nevada/\n  | accessdate = 2009-02-01\n  | edition = 10th\n  | origyear = 1872\n  | year = 1902\n  | chapter = Chapter XIII Mount Whitney\n  | chapterurl = http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/mountaineering_in_the_sierra_nevada/13.html\n  | isbn = 0-585-27432-0 }}</ref> Just a month earlier, on August 18, 1873, Charles Begole, A. H. Johnson, and John Lucas, all of nearby [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]], had become the first to reach the highest summit in the contiguous United States. As they climbed the mountain during a fishing trip to nearby Kern Canyon, they called the mountain Fisherman's Peak.<ref name=\"Farquhar\"/>\n\nIn 1881 [[Samuel Pierpont Langley]], founder of the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] remained for some time on the summit, making daily observations on the solar heat.<ref name=ea>{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Whitney, Mount}}</ref> Accompanying Langley in 1881 was another party consisting of Judge William B. Wallace of Visalia, W. A. Wright and Reverend Frederick Wales.<ref name=\"seq\">\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.sequoiaparksfoundation.org/2012/historic-people-and-places-william-b-wallace/\n |accessdate  = 2015-10-04\n |title       = Historic People And Places: WILLIAM B. WALLACE\n |publisher   = Sequoia Parks Foundation\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120904001136/http://www.sequoiaparksfoundation.org/2012/historic-people-and-places-william-b-wallace/\n |archivedate = 2012-09-04\n}}</ref> Wallace later wrote in his memoirs<ref name = \"paiute\">\n  {{cite book\n  | last = Wallace\n  | first = William B.\n  | chapter = A Night On Mt. Whitney\n  | title = Mt. Whitney Club Journal\n  | year = 1902\n  | volume = 1\n  | issue = 1\n  | pages = 8\u20139\n  | publisher = Mt. Whitney Club\n  | location = Visalia, CA\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=Q35LAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=\"Too-man-i-goo-yah\"#v=onepage&q=\"Too-man-i-goo-yah\"&f=false }}\n</ref> that \"The [[Northern Paiute| Pi Ute [Paiute] ]] Indians called Mt. Whitney \"''Too-man-i-goo-yah'',\" which means \"the very old man.\" They believe that the Great Spirit who presides over the destiny of their people once had his home in that mountain.\"  The spelling ''Too-man-i-goo-yah'' is a transliteration from the indigenous Paiute [[Mono language (California)|Mono language]]. Other variations are ''Too-man-go-yah''<ref name = \"14ers\">\n  {{cite book\n  | title = Climbing California's Fourteeners: The Route Guide to the Fifteen Highest Peaks\n  | first1 = Stephen\n  | last1 = Porcella\n  | first2 = Cameron\n  | last2 = Burns\n  | publisher = [[The Mountaineers (club)#Mountaineers Books|Mountaineers Books]]\n  | page = 55\n  | isbn = 0-89886-555-7\n  | date = 1998\n  | url = https://books.google.com/?id=uM6amm4BDtAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Climbing+California's+Fourteeners:#v=onepage&q=too%20man&f=false}}\n</ref> and  ''Tumanguya''.<ref name = \"bustle\">\n {{ cite web\n  | url = http://www.bustle.com/articles/107621-5-whitewashed-american-landmarks-that-like-mount-mckinley-sorely-need-a-name-change\n  | website = www.bustle.com\n  |  title = 5 Whitewashed American Landmarks That, Like Mount McKinley, Sorely Need A Name Change\n  | first = Lauren\n  | last = Barbato\n  | date = 2015-08-31  }}\n</ref>\n\n[[File:Smithsonian Hut Whitney.jpg|thumb|The [[Smithsonian Institution Shelter]] on Whitney's summit]]\nIn 1891, the [[United States Geological Survey]]'s Board on Geographic Names decided to recognize the earlier name Mount Whitney.  Despite losing out on their preferred name, residents of Lone Pine financed the first trail to the summit, engineered by Gustave Marsh, and completed on July 22, 1904. Just four days later, the new trail enabled the first recorded death on Whitney. Having hiked the trail, [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|U.S. Bureau of Fisheries]] employee Byrd Surby was struck and killed by lightning while eating lunch on the exposed summit. In response to this event, Marsh began work on the stone hut that would become the [[Smithsonian Institution Shelter]], and completed it in 1909.<ref name=\"LPC\">\n  {{cite web\n |url=http://www.lonepinechamber.org/history/whitneyhist2.html\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211171515/http://www.lonepinechamber.org/history/whitneyhist2.html\n |archivedate=2012-02-11\n |work=Mount Whitney History\n |title=Mt. Whitney's Early Days\n |publisher=Lone Pine Chamber of Commerce\n |accessdate=2009-02-01\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nA movement began after [[World War&nbsp;II]] to rename the mountain for [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis |id=269051 |name=Mount Whitney |accessdate=2009-02-01}}</ref>  However, the name Mount Whitney has persisted.\n\n==Climbing routes==\n\n=== Trails ===\n[[File:Whitney trail at night.jpg|thumb|Long-exposure photograph of hikers ascending before sunrise]]\nThe most popular route to the summit is by way of the [[Mount Whitney Trail]] which starts at [[Whitney Portal]], at an elevation of {{convert|8360|ft|abbr=on}}, {{convert|13|mi|abbr=on}} west of the town of [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]].  The hike is about {{convert|22|mi|km|abbr=on}} round trip with an elevation gain of over {{convert|6100|ft|abbr=on}}. Permits are required year round, and to prevent overuse a limited number of permits are issued by the [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] between May 1 and November 1.<ref>\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/inyo/recreation/wild/mtwhitney.shtml\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080414042448/http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/inyo/recreation/wild/mtwhitney.shtml\n  | archivedate = 2008-04-14\n  | title = Recreational Activities - Mt. Whitney\n  | publisher = US Forest Service\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-09 }}</ref> The Forest Service holds an annual lottery for hiking and backpacking permits on the Mount Whitney Trail. Applications are accepted from February 1 through March 15. Any permits left over after the lottery is completed typically go on sale April 1. Most hikers plan to stay one or two nights camping along the route.<ref>\n  {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/inyo/passes-permits/recreation/?cid=stelprdb5150055\n  | title = Mount Whitney Lottery - Permit Reservations\n  | publisher = US Forest Service\n  | accessdate = 2014-01-23 }}</ref> Those in good physical condition sometimes attempt to reach the summit and return to Whitney Portal in one day. A single day hike requires a \"day use\" permit that prohibits the use of overnight camping gear (sleeping bag and tent). Day hikers often leave Whitney Portal before sunrise and hike from 12 to 18 hours round trip.<ref name=dayhiker/>\n\nLonger approaches to Whitney arrive at its west side, connecting to the Mount Whitney Trail near the summit by way of the [[John Muir Trail]].\n\n=== Scrambles ===\n[[File:Mt. Whitney and south-eastern Sierra Nevada aerial.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Mount Whitney and the steep eastern side of the Sierra Nevada, from the north]]\nThe \"Mountaineer's Route\", a gully on the north side of the east face first climbed by [[John Muir]], is considered a [[scrambling|scramble]], {{YDS|3}} ([[Grade (climbing)#International French Adjectival System (IFAS)|PD+]]).<ref name=\"Secor\">{{cite Secor |pages=70\u201375}}</ref> The fastest recorded time up this route to the summit and back to the portal is 3 hours 10 minutes, by Jason Lakey of Bishop.<ref name=rockice/>\n\n=== Technical climbs ===\nThe steep eastern side of the mountain offers a variety of [[climbing]] challenges. The [[East Face (Mount Whitney)|East Face]] route, first climbed in 1931, is one of the ''[[Fifty Classic Climbs of North America]]'' [[climbing route|route]]s and involves technical [[free climbing]] ({{YDS|5.7}}) but is mostly class 4.  Other routes range up to grade 5.10d.<ref name=\"Secor\"/>\n\nSouth of the main summit there are a series of minor summits that are completely inconspicuous from the west but appear as a series of \"needles\" from the east. The routes on these include some of the finest big-wall climbing in the high Sierra. Two of the needles were named after participants in an 1880 scientific expedition to the mountain. Keeler Needle was named for [[James Edward Keeler|James Keeler]] and Day Needle was named for William Cathcart Day. The latter has now been renamed Crooks Peak after [[Hulda Crooks]] who hiked up Mount Whitney every year until well into her nineties.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Mountains|California}}}}\n* [[List of mountain peaks of California]]\n* [[List of highest points in California by county]]\n* [[List of U.S. states by elevation]]\n* [[List of the highest major summits of the United States]]\n* [[List of the most prominent summits of the United States]]\n* [[List of the most isolated major summits of the United States]]\n* [[Whitney Classic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=dayhiker>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.dayhiker.com/directory/MtWhitney.htm|title=Mt. Whitney \u2013 One Day Hike\n   |publisher=dayhiker.com |accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Farquhar\">\n  {{cite book |last=Farquhar |first=Francis P. |authorlink=Francis P. Farquhar\n  |title=Place Names of the High Sierra\n  |url=http://www.yosemite.ca.us/library/place_names_of_the_high_sierra/w.html\n  |accessdate=2007-08-12 |publisher=[[Sierra Club]]\n  |location=[[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]\n  |year=1926}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ngs\">\n  {{cite ngs |id=GT1811 |name=Whitney |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n<ref name=ngs_hcm>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.ngs.noaa.gov/TOOLS/Vertcon/vert_method.html\n  |title=Height Conversion Methodology |publisher=U.S. National Geodetic Survey\n  |accessdate=2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Peakbagger\">\n  {{cite peakbagger |pid=2829|name=Mount Whitney, California |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Peakbagger_KeyCol\">\n  {{cite peakbagger |kid=2829|name=Playas Valley/Pride Draw Saddle |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=rockice>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.rockandice.com/news/1272-bishop-local-adds-513b-crack-and-speed-solos-whitney-region\n  |title=Bishop Local Adds 5.13b Crack, And Speed Solos Whitney Region\n  |publisher=Rock and Ice |date=December 9, 2010\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212234615/http://www.rockandice.com/news/1272-bishop-local-adds-513b-crack-and-speed-solos-whitney-region\n  |archivedate=2010-12-12}}</ref>\n<ref name=usfs_sn>\n  {{cite web |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/projects/ecoregions/m261e.htm\n  |title=Sierra Nevada\n  |work=Ecological Subregions of California\n  |publisher=[[United States Forest Service|US Forest Service]]\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601101102/http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/projects/ecoregions/m261e.htm\n  |archivedate=2008-06-01\n  |accessdate=2008-04-09 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Doug\n  | author2=Elisabeth Newbold\n  | title = Mount Whitney: Mountain Lore from the Whitney Store\n  | publisher = Westwind Publishing Company\n  | year = 1997\n  | isbn =  978-0-9653596-0-3 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons and category|Mount Whitney}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Mount Whitney}}\n\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/inyo/recarea/?recid=20806\n  |title=Mt. Whitney Trail\n  |publisher=Inyo National Forest}}\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.whitneyzone.com/wz/\n  |title=Mt Whitney Hikers Association\n  |accessdate=}}\n* {{cite web\n  |url=http://www.whitneyportalstore.com\n  |title=Whitney Portal Store}}\n* {{cite summitpost |id=150227 |name=Mount Whitney}}\n* {{cite NIE |title=Whitney, Mount |year=1905}}\n\n{{NA highest}}{{NA prominent}}{{NA isolated}}\n{{California highest}}\n{{California Fourteeners}}\n{{U.S. State Highest Points}}\n{{Sequoia National Park}}\n{{California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitney, Mount}}\n[[Category:Fourteeners of California]]\n[[Category:Highest points of U.S. states]]\n[[Category:Inyo National Forest]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Inyo County, California]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Sequoia National Park]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the John Muir Wilderness]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Tulare County, California]]\n[[Category:Symbols of California]]\n[[Category:Highest points of United States national parks]]\n[[Category:North American 4000 m summits|Mount Whitney]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Northern California]]\n", "name_user": "98.221.82.90", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Whitney"}
